<HEAD>Names in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS last item to CORRECT that Emory is in Atlanta sted Decatur.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY14</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Indigo Girls say their brand of
folk-rock music isn't necessarily part of a return-to-roots
movement among pop performers.
   ``I don't know if we're big enough to be part of a trend,'' Amy
Ray said in a recent interview. ``I think once every 15 years
acoustic music gets popular again. But we never thought of acoustic
music not being popular.''
   Ray and her partner, Emily Saliers, have been getting
unaccustomed attention since their debut album, ``Indigo Girls,''
went gold two weeks ago.
   The childhood friends from Decatur, Ga., began collaborating
when they were in high school and became the Indigo Girls while
students at Emory University in Atlanta.
   Ray said her listening tastes lean more toward rock 'n' roll,
while Saliers favors the acoustic sound.
