<FIRST>r a PM-Hugo-Riley     10-09 0488</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hugo-Riley,0504</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mayor Praised for Organizing Relief Efforts After Hugo</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE SMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Joseph P. Riley Jr. was somber as
the 135-mph winds of Hurricane Hugo roared outside, wrenching the
tin roof off Charleston's antebellum City Hall.
   ``All we can do now is pray,'' he said quietly to a handful of
staff and reporters gathered in his candlelit office to ride out
the storm.
   From that dark hour, the 46-year-old mayor emerged as a symbol
of the determination with which residents are digging out from the
Sept. 21 hurricane, the worst storm to hit South Carolina in a
century.
   He organized a relief effort which brought tons of supplies and
hundreds of thousands of dollars to Charleston, much of which was
sent to storm-ravaged areas miles from the city.
   He also imposed a curfew to prevent looting and took quick steps
to prevent price gouging.
   ``He was there the entire time. He was in the shelters and he
was always there with the people,'' said Susie Crosby, a paralegal.
   Sara Joyner, an administrative secretary at a law firm, agreed.
``He was totally in charge,'' she said.
   Riley worked 18-hour days through the clean-up effort and
fielded hundreds of questions daily from the media. He was sharply
critical of the federal response to the disaster, blasting the
Federal Emergency Management Agency for what he said was an
inadequate response.
   FEMA officials blasted Riley back, and Mark Chambers, a
spokesman for Gov. Carroll Campbell, defended FEMA's efforts.
``FEMA is providing everything the state of South Carolina needs.
We're talking about one of the most devastating storms in recent
history. It's being done,'' he said.
   That storm has mostly passed. Now, the mayor is spending much of
his time urging tourists to return to the 319-year-old city. He
said the city has bounced back.
   In an interview last week, he wore a T-shirt proclaiming
``Charleston, S.C., Going Strong.'' Scattered around room were
cards and letters from people moved by Charleston's plight.
   Riley, who has served as mayor for more than a decade, had urged
residents a day before Hugo struck to evacuate low-lying areas. He
directed his staff to contact mayors of cities hit by hurricanes in
recent years to pick their minds about preparations.
   Hurricane Hugo toppled dozens of buildings in the city and
damaged about 80 percent of the roofs. But Riley said the miracle
is that so few lives were lost _ only one in the Charleston.
Seventeen other deaths across the state were attributed to the
storm.
   ``This hurricane had blood on its mind,'' Riley said.
   Throughout the ordeal, Riley said his most enduring impression
of the storm was the courage of his fellow Charlestonians.
   ``People who lost homes say they're lucky to be alive. People
who lost a roof say they're lucky to have a house. The people are
courageous, and thankful and spirited,'' the mayor said.
</TEXT>
