<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets     10-09 0273</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0283</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Down, Stocks Up In Tokyo</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar eased slightly against the Japanese yen
Monday, while share prices on the Tokyo Stock Exchange gained
ground.
   The dollar closed at 142.23 yen, down 0.22 yen from Friday's
close of 142.45 yen. After opening at 141.60 yen, the currency
moved in a range of 141.60-142.28 yen.
   On the stock market, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected
issues, a 313.64-point loser Friday, won back 167.00 points, or
0.47 percent, to close at 35,376.35.
   Currency dealers said the dollar's slump followed a U.S. Labor
Department report Friday that the nation's unemployment rate rose
to 5.3 percent in Semptember from 5.2 percent in both July and
August.
   ``The market now is a bit concerned about a possible move'' by
the Federal Reserve Bank of New York to lower its federal fund
rates, said a dealer with the Bank of Tokyo on condition of
anonymity.
   Another dealer at Daiichi Kangyo Bank said: ``Now that the
incentive to buy the dollar is calming down it is uncertain whether
the Bank of Japan will continue to give upward pressure on interest
rates. Either way, the dollar is expected to remain bullish'' in
the long run.
   Securities dealers said investors were reacting favorably to the
strengthening yen early Monday.
   ``The environment is sound, but with a national holiday the next
day, we can't really expect much of market activities today,'' said
a dealer at a major Japanese securities firm, requesting anonymity.
   Banks, government offices, foreign exchanges and stock markets
and many businesses will be closed Tuesday, Oct.10, for Sports Day,
a national holiday in Japan.
