<FIRST>d a PM-BRF--Harvard-AIDS     10-09 0144</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Harvard-AIDS,0148</SECOND>
<HEAD>Harvard Establishes AIDS Research Center</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Harvard will establish a $38.6 million
clearing house for AIDS research at the university's school for
public health.
   The Statistical and Data Analysis Center for the AIDS Clinical
Trials Group will compile information from and design proposals for
research at 45 institutions and more than 100 clinics across the
country.
   ``The center provides an essential link to getting data analyzed
and reported as quickly as possible,'' said Dr. Marcia A. Testa, a
lecturer at the school and director of one of the center's three
divisions.
   The National Institute for Health will fund the center with a
five-year grant, said Leslie Fink, a spokesperson for the National
Institute of Allergies and Infectious Diseases, the NIH division
overseeing the project.
   Fink said NIH chose Harvard from a national competition, The
Harvard Crimson reported Saturday.
