<FILEID>AP-NR-10-09-89 0343EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Colombia     10-09 0549</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Colombia,0573</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Find Body Of Official; Justice Minister Takes Office</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STAN YARBRO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police found the bullet-riddled body of
the Medellin army commander's private secretary stashed in a car
just hours after the president swore in a new justice minister and
two other Cabinet officers.
   Nury Velasquez de Vasquez was kidnapped Friday in Medellin,
Colombia's cocaine center, and her body was found Sunday 10 miles
to the northwest, in Marinilla. No group claimed responsibility for
the slaying.
   The Medellin army brigade has been active in confiscating
properties allegedly belonging to traffickers. The confiscations
are part of the government's 2-month-old crackdown on the country's
cocaine barons.
   Colombia's new justice minister, Roberto Salazar Manrique, is
the ninth to serve under President Virgilio Barco. He was sworn in
along with Interior Minister Carlos Lemos Simmonds and
Communications Minister Enrique Danies Rincones.
   Salazar, a graduate of Notre Dame University, replaces Monica de
Greiff, 32, who resigned after death threats from drug traffickers
during the 70 days she served in office.
   Shortly after taking office, Salazar told reporters he did not
fear traffickers, who are thought to have killed former Justice
Minister Rodrigo Lara Bonilla in 1984.
   He reiterated his pledge to carry out ``firmly and fairly'' the
extradition of Colombian drug suspects to the United States, where
many face trafficking and money-laundering charges.
   In Colombia, drug barons have operated with relative impunity by
paying off or intimidating judges.
   The new justice minister faces the difficult task of pushing
forward the unprecedented government crackdown, which Barco
declared a day after traffickers assassinated the leading
presidential contender.
   In retaliation, traffickers declared war on the government.
Since mid-August, 148 bombings and arson attacks have killed 10
people and injured 164 in Bogota, the capital, and Medellin.
   In commencing the crackdown, Barco issued emergency decrees
allowing the extradition of cocaine barons and the seizure of their
property.
   He has said he will not negotiate with traffickers, who want to
hold talks with the government on its new extradition policy.
   But in newspaper interviews published Sunday, a former interior
minister said he carried messages from the Medellin Cartel _ the
world's largest drug trafficking organization _ to a top aide to
Barco.
   The El Tiempo newspaper quoted Joaquin Vallejo as saying that
although there were no direct negotiations, the president's general
secretary, German Montoya, did not discourage indirect contacts
with traffickers.
   Vallejo said Montoya, who apparently acted on orders from Barco,
was willing to consider negotiations if the United States agreed to
participate. U.S. government opposition made talks impossible,
Vallejo said.
   In a communique, Montoya said his decision to meet with Vallejo
was a personal one and that he told the former interior minister a
dialogue between the government and the cartel was impossible.
   Also Sunday, an explosion and fire killed seven people and
injured eight on a Bogota bus. Police initially said they thought
it was caused by an incendiary bomb but later said that theory was
in question.
   The radio network Caracol quoted a policeman at the scene as
saying the fire originated from a five-gallon plastic container
filled with gasoline that had been carried by a passenger.
   Three children were among the victims, who struggled in vain to
climb out of the burning bus, police said.
</TEXT>
