<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Markets     10-09 0334</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0346</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Down, Stocks Up In Tokyo</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar fell slightly against the Japanese yen
today, contributing to a gain by the Tokyo Stock Exchange's main
index.
   The dollar closed at 142.23 yen, down 0.22 yen from its close of
142.45 yen last Friday, when it rose 1.40 yen. The dollar opened
today at 141.60 yen, its low for the day, and ranged as high as
142.28 yen.
   Currency dealers said the dollar's decline followed a Washington
Labor Department report on Friday that the U.S. unemployment rate
rose to 5.3 percent in September from 5.2 percent in July and
August.
   They said this might encourage the Federal Reserve Board to
lower interest rates, which would tend to make the dollar less
attractive to foreign investors.
   But a dealer at Daiichi Kangyo Bank said the dollar was expected
to keep its strength in the long run.
   ``Now that the incentive to buy the dollar is calming down, it
is uncertain whether the Bank of Japan will continue to put upward
pressure on (Japanese) interest rates,'' said the dealer, on
condition of anonymity.
   He said the announcement of the latest U.S. consumer price index
later this week likely will give the market a direction.
   On the stock market, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected
issues, a 313.64-point loser on Friday, regained 167.00 points, or
0.47 percent, closing at 35,376.35.
   Securities dealers attributed the rebound to the dollar' easing
against the Japanese yen.
   ``Investors were reacting favorably to the strengthening of the
yen today,'' said a dealer at Nikko Securities Co., on condition of
anonymity.
   Another dealer said, ``the environment is sound, but with a
national holiday the next day, we can't really expect much market
activity today.''
   Volume traded on the first section of the exchange, where major
shares are listed, was estimated at 700 million shares.
   Banks, government offices, foreign exchange and stock markets
and many businesses will be closed Tuesday for Sports Day, a
national holiday in Japan.
</TEXT>
