<FIRST>r a PM-BiasBeating     10-09 0367</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bias Beating,0378</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jewish Students Attacked By Gang in Brooklyn</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A gang of youths shouthing ethnic slurs set upon
three young Jewish men emerging from a party at a Jewish student
center and beat them severely, leaving two in serious condition,
authorities said.
   The police department's bias unit was investigating the
incident, which took place on the eve of the solemn Jewish holiday
of Yom Kippur, said Sgt. Diane Kubler, a police spokesman.
   The attack prompted an immediate outcry from community leaders.
   ``They came out of a fraternity party and were set upon by about
15 white youths who called them names and then beat the daylights
out of them,'' said city Councilman Noach Dear of Brooklyn.
   ``They were beating up anybody who wasn't of their kind,'' he
said.
   Two Brooklyn College freshmen were beaten just after midnight
Saturday when they emerged from a party at the Hillel House Jewish
student center near the college campus, Kubler SAID. A third man
was beaten when he came upon the gang and told them to stop, Dear
said.
   Dear identified the two students as Joshua Fogel and Steven
Weisburg, both freshmen at the college.
   Mayor Edward I. Koch and Dear visited the students at Kings
County Hospital. Dear said Fogel had a fractured skull and Weisburg
had a ruptured spleen, which was removed, a broken leg and injuries
to one of his knees.
   Police said Weisburg was listed in serious condition. Fogel was
in stable condition. The third victim, Steve Eilat, did not need to
be admitted to the hospital, police said.
   Yom Kippur, the day of atonement for Jews, started at sunset
Sunday.
   Dear said the young men had been told recently by their parents
not to wear their yarmulkes, or religious skullcaps, late at night
because of the possibility of attacks.
   ``It's unbelievable. We're living in a society where you have to
hide your religious beliefs,'' Dear said. ``That reminds me of Nazi
Germany. If I have to hide who I am, this is a terrible society.''
   ``I knew I wasn't supposed to wear the yarmulke, but I thought:
Why not? I'm going to Hillel House, that's my home territory,''
Weisburg said.
</TEXT>
