<HEAD>Eds: SUBS MONROE, Mich.-dated 2nd item to CORRECT spelling of ginkgo
sted gingko in 1st-4th grafs.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MONROE, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   While most Michigan residents enjoy the
turning of the fall colors, people in Monroe hold their noses as
the ginkgo tree turns rank.
   The ginkgo dates back 200 million years to the era of dinosaurs.
And, residents say, every fall it smells like it.
   ``It smells just like a baby's dirty pants. Really!'' said Marie
McNairn, a member of the Friends of Dorsch Library. ``I smelled it
for years.''
   Since 1865, a ginkgo has been standing in front of the Dorsch
library in this town 30 miles southwest of Detroit.
   The female tree, which originates from eastern China, bears an
edible fruit whose hull emits a strong odor into the fall air.
   Monroe's annual Ginkgo Mania festival, which began last week,
includes a contest to determine what day the Dorsch tree's leaves
will fall. Ginkgoes shed their leaves in a matter of hours.
   Robert Peven, a Monroe County Planning Department employee by
day but a ginkgo maniac by night, tried to write a poem about the
ginkgo but gave up after realizing the only rhyming word is stinko.
   Instead, he found a passage in a Japanese poetry anthology and
read it at a meeting of the Dorsch Friends Club:
   ``Treading the fallen leaves of the ginkgo tree, the boy comes
down the mount.''
   Maxine Lahti, one of 18 in attendance, concluded: ``There's just
so much that can be said about a ginkgo tree!''
</TEXT>
