<SECOND>PM-Newspage-Baseball,0271</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oakland Advances to World Series; San Francisco Takes 3-1 Lead Over
Cubs</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: RETRANSMITTING to fix category code.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos CP2, CP3, CP4, FX1, FXP1, FXP2, LaserColor CP1</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With Rickey Henderson running the show, the
Oakland Athletics are returning to baseball's World Series for the
second year in a row.
   The A's beat the Toronto Blue Jays, 4-3, Sunday to win the
American League playoffs in five games.
   Henderson, who began his career with the Athletics and was
traded back to his hometown by the New York Yankees in June, made
the playoff series his personal showcase and was named Most
Valuable Player.
   He reached base in 14 of 23 plate appearances and stole a
postseason series record eight bases. He also hit two home runs, a
triple, a double and scored eight times.
   ``I can't say I surprised myself,'' said Henderson, not known
for his modesty.
   In Sunday's game, Dave Stewart outpitched Dave Stieb for the
second time in the playoffs. That made Oakland became the first
team to win consecutive pennants since the Yankees and Los Angeles
each did it in 1977-78.
   The Athletics will open the World Series at home next Saturday
against San Francisco or Chicago. The Giants beat the Cubs 6-4
Sunday to take a 3-1 lead in the National League playoffs. Game 5
is scheduled for this afternoon.
   If the Giants win, it will set up a cross-bay series, the first
time in 33 years that a metropolitan area monopolized the World
Series. In 1956, the New York Yankees defeated the Brooklyn Dodgers.
