<FIRST>r i PM-NorthernIreland     10-09 0528</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Northern Ireland,0547</SECOND>
<HEAD>Four Charged in Probe Linked With Assassination of IRA Members</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police investigating security
leaks arrested 28 members of the army's Ulster Defense Regiment in
raids on their homes and four were charged with unspecified
firearms offenses.
   The soldiers allegedly leaked files identifying IRA members some
of whom were targeted for assassination by Protestant extremists,
police said.
   Some of those detained in the raids early Sunday were later
released, and it was not clear whether others would be charged.
Police said they found security documents, ammunition and weapons
in the raids.
   The four charged with unspecified firearms offenses were to
appear in court today.
   The Ulster Defense Regiment is part of the British Army and
consists of soldiers who belong overwhelmingly to the Protestant
majority.
   The predominantly Roman Catholic IRA has killed 180 members of
the regiment in its fight to end British rule and unite Northern
Ireland with the Irish Republic.
   Members of the regiment and police officers of the Royal Ulster
Constabulary allegedly colluded with outlawed Protestant groups by
giving them copies of lists of Irish Republican Army suspects.
   Loughlin Maginn, 28, a Catholic father of four who was on one of
the leaked lists, was assassinated Aug. 25 and two members of the
regiment have been charged in his slaying. The killing was claimed
by the Ulster Freedom Fighters, an outlawed Protestant group, which
claimed Maginn was in the IRA.
   Sunday's arrests came after an inquiry by John Stevens, a
regional police chief brought in from England. His probe was
triggered by the Ulster Freedom Fighters giving security details of
Maginn and other persons to the press.
   A British soldier, brought from his base in Dortmund, West
Germany, has already been charged with leaking information.
   Early today, a man was killed by a gunman who pulled up
alongside him in a car and shot him at point-blank range, police
said. The man, whose name was released, was shot in County
Londonderry, the Royal Ulster Constabulary said.
   The victim had no connection with the security forces in
Northern Ireland, said a police spokesman on condition of anonymity.
   In another development, police said they foiled a planned
breakout of IRA prisoners from Belfast's Crumlin Road jail on
Saturday night. They said four pounds of plastic explosives were
found at the prison and a 500-pound bomb was defused on a
construction site outside the facility.
   Rioting in Belfast Saturday night appeared designed to keep
officers busy while the escape proceeded, police said. They said
seven stolen cars were left at the prison with ignition keys inside.
   Brendan Curren, a councilman for Sinn Fein, the legal political
wing of the IRA, was shot and wounded by unidentified gunmen Sunday
night in Lurgan, 20 miles southwest of Belfast.
   Earlier Sunday, police superintendent Alwyn Harris, 51, was
killed by a bomb when he started his car in Lisburn, 10 miles west
of Belfast. No group claimed responsibility.
   The killings brought the Northern Ireland death toll since the
first killings in 1969 to 2,759, according to police count. The
dead include 264 police officers, 597 British Army and Ulster
Defense Regiment and 1,899 civilians.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
