<FIRST>r i PM-Pope-Asia     10-09 0436</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pope-Asia,0452</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pope Arrives as `Friend' in World's Largest Moslem Country</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: One name cq for Suharto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTOR L. SIMPSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II began a visit to the
world's largest Moslem country today and said Indonesia's tiny
Roman Catholic minority seeks unity with all Indonesians.
   The pope's remarks came amid controversy over a scheduled stop
in East Timor, a predominantly Catholic Portuguese territory
annexed by Indonesia in 1976.
   The pope arrived after a weekend visit to Seoul, South Korea.
The pontiff knelt and kissed the tarmac, wet from a tropical
rainstorm, in the sticky 90 degree heat.
   Soldiers lined the 10-mile motorcade route from the military
airport to the palm tree-ringed presidential palace, where
Indonesia's pro-Western president, Suharto, greeted the pontiff.
There have been several reported threats on the life of the pope
from Moslem extremist groups.
   In a country made up of 13,766 islands and about 200 ethnic and
religious groups, Indonesian governments have stressed the need to
maintain unity.
   John Paul immediately sought to make clear that his visit posed
no threat to unity in this nation of 5 million Catholics and 157
million Moslems.
   During a Mass at a sports stadium, the pope said he came as ``a
friend of every Indonesian in our common humanity and our common
concern for the development and peace of the world in which we
live.''
   He expressed his ``cordial esteem'' to ``our Moslem brothers and
sisters, who are so numerous in this country.''
   ``I extend the hand of sincere and heartfelt friendship in our
common belief in the one God, our creator and merciful lord,'' the
pope said, speaking in English.
   John Paul said Catholic Indonesians were deeply proud of their
country.
   ``We must be fully Catholic and fully Indonesian,'' the pope
said. ``These words are deeply inscribed in the modern history of
the nation.''
   The stop in East Timor, scheduled for Thursday, has drawn
protests from Portugal, but John Paul has said the visit does not
imply Vatican recognition of Indonesia's annexation of the
territory.
   He said last week that skipping the territory would be an
``offense'' to East Timor's Catholics, nearly 80 percent of the
island's 690,000 people.
   The 69-year-old pontiff is to spend five days in Indonesia and
visit four cities in addition to the capital.
   During his two-day visit to South Korea, he encouraged people to
work toward unifying the Korean Peninsula.
   Korea was the first stop on the pope's 10-day Asian tour. He
also is to visit the Indian Ocean island nation of Mauritius before
returning to Rome on Oct. 16.
</TEXT>
