<FIRST>r i AM-HongKong-China     10-09 0286</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hong Kong-China,0293</SECOND>
<HEAD>China Refuses to Accept Illegal Immigrants For First Time</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China for the first time has refused to accept
70 Chinese illegal immigrants being returned from Hong Kong, a
government spokesman said Monday.
   The immigrants were scheduled to be repatriated to the
neighboring Chinese province of Guandong on Sunday, but Chinese
officials refused to accept them at the border checkpoint,
according to the official, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   He said Hong Kong has begun talks with Chinese officials on the
issue.
   Hong Kong has been sending back all illegal immigrants from
China since 1980. Previously, only those caught at the border were
repatriated.
   More than 12,000 illegal immigrants were repatriated to China
this year, the spokesman said.
   On Wednesday, Beijing criticized Hong Kong for permitting
Chinese swimmer Yang Yang to leave for the United States after he
was released from a detention center under a discretionary section
of the immigration code. He had been arrested Sept. 23 for having
an expired visa.
   The swimmer had unsuccessfully sought political asylum in Hong
Kong, saying he feared Chinese authorities would jail him for
joining in pro-democracy marches in the colony.
   China's official Xinhua News Agency said Hong Kong had set a bad
precedent in the case. It said the action ``will surely adversely
relations between the two sides in other fields. Only the Hong Kong
government should be responsible for all the consequences.''
   Hong Kong reverts to Chinese rule in 1997, and China has
promised it will retain the territory's legal and capitalistic
systems for 50 years after the takeover. Confidence in the colony's
future suffered a setback when Chinese troops crushed a
pro-democracy movement in Beijing in June.
</TEXT>
