<FILEID>AP-NR-10-09-89 1229EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Romania     10-09 0445</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Romania,0461</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ceausescu Tours Bucharest Markets, Promises Better Food Supplies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Romanian leader Nicolae Ceausescu has
toured poorly stocked markets in Bucharest and promised better food
supplies, a news agency reported Monday.
   Agerpres said Ceausescu, whose unexpected visit of food outlets
in Romania's capital on Sunday came just a day after returning from
celebrations in East Germany, announced improvements in
government-sponsored food programs.
   There has been growing criticism of food shortages in Romania,
as well as recent unofficial calls for Ceausescu to step down.
   ``The programs of good supply to the population should be
extended and developed,'' the report said, without elaborating.
   Under Ceausescu's centralized economy, Romania _ once the
breadbasket of Eastern Europe _ has faced rationing of staples such
as meat, flour, cooking oil and bread, while fresh vegetables and
fruit have been hard to find even in spring and summer.
   Sugar has been rationed to 2.2 pounds per person per month and
cooking oil to one quart per person a month.
   Last month, the government announced that starting Oct. 1, oil
and sugar supplies would be augmented by 20 percent and 15 percent,
respectively.
   Most of Romania's farmland is owned by state collective farms
and only 10 percent is tilled privately in small plots or gardens
around farmers' houses.
   ``The visit and the analysis that followed disclosed the
steadfast preoccupation of the ... leadeship with the ... rhythmic
supply of ... markets ... to the planned extent and at an
appropriate level of quality,'' Agerpres said.
   Delegates to a Romanian Communist Party congress scheduled for
next month have been urged recently to denounce Ceausescu for
incompetence and oust him as party leader.
   Ceausescu, 71, was unanimously proposed by the party's
policy-setting Central Committee in the summer to be re-elected at
the Nov. 20-25 congress.
   Addressing a party meeting of economic experts last week, he
made clear that under his hard-line rule, Romania would never adopt
economic and political reforms under way in Hungary, Poland and the
Soviet Union.
   In an unusually harsh criticism, the government daily Romania
Libera blamed transportation problems, bad organization and
careless administration for the food shortages.
   ``A large crowd was waiting in line at the vegetables counter of
Titan market, although nothing was on sale,'' the newspaper said.
   Asked about the absence of fresh vegetables, market officials
said ``only 19 metric tons of potatoes were delivered out of the
planned 25 tons, while deliveries of carrots, eggplants and greens
remained only on paper.''
   ``Only once we received pears (from state-owned farms) this
summer,'' the officials told Romania Libera.
   ``After you tour 10-15 markets you can conclude that ...
distribution is wrongly done,'' it said.
</TEXT>
