<FIRST>r a PM-EngineFailure     10-09 0231</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Engine Failure,0235</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pan Am 747 Makes Emergency Landing After Engine Failure</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Pan American World Airways jumbo jet bound
from New York to Madrid made an emergency landing in Newfoundland,
Canada, after one of its four engines failed early today, airline
spokesmen said.
   Flight 156, a Boeing 747, landed at Gander, Newfoundland, about
3:20 a.m. EDT. No one was injured, but hotels were unavailable and
all but two of the 203 passengers spent the night at the terminal
or aboard the airplane.
   Those two chartered a private jet, while the others continued
their trip aboard a substitute 747 that left Gander at 10:30 a.m.,
said Alan Loflin, a spokesman for Pan Am.
   The original flight, with a crew of 17, left John F. Kennedy
International Airport about 9:50 p.m. Sunday. Near Gander ``they
experienced an engine vibration and a stall and the No. 1 engine
was shut down,'' said Elizabeth Manners, a Pan Am spokeswoman.
   While a 747 can fly on three of its four engines, normal
procedure in such cases is to land at the nearest airport. The
pilot declared ``a routine, precautionary emergency'' to gain
priority to land at Gander, Loflin said.
   The plane descended from about 33,000 feet in what Loflin called
``a deliberate descent'' but not a disruptive one. The plane landed
safely and passengers departed by portable stairs, he said.
</TEXT>
