<SECOND>AM-BRF--Soviet-Airport,0150</SECOND>
<HEAD>Latvian Airport Given International Status</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government has given Riga airport
international status and it will begin serving foreign carriers
next year, Tass said Monday.
   ``The runways, radio-navigation and other facilities can receive
and dispatch planes under any weather conditions and provide prompt
and efficient service to passengers,'' the official news agency
said.
   Tass said that in the past three or four years, the number of
tourists and business people traveling to the Latvian capital has
tripled.
   ``The first Riga-Stockholm line will open in 1990,'' Tass said.
An agreement between the state-run airline Aeroflot and the
Scandinavian carrier SAS has been signed, providing for three
flights a week, the report said.
   Regular flights between Riga and Helsinki, Finland, also are to
begin in 1990, Tass said.
   Eleven other Soviet airports have international status,
including Kiev, Leningrad, Tashkent and Minsk.
