<FIRST>r a AM-Cavazos-Indians     10-09 0230</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cavazos-Indians,0236</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cavazos Announces New Study Of Indian Schools</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's top educator has announced
the beginning of a nationwide study of American Indian schooling
that he hopes will help change decades of disappointing academic
performance.
   ``You may say, `We've been studying this problem for 200 years.
Why another study?''' Secretary of Education Lauro Cavazos said
Sunday. ``But you have to start thinking about what we don't know.
Just by calling attention to it, hopefully, we can bring America to
focus on this problem.
   ``With luck, maybe, by the turn of the century, we'll start
turning the corner.''
   Cavazos spoke at the kickoff meeting of the National Indian
Education Association's 21st annual conference, scheduled through
Thursday. About 1,400 American Indian educators from across the
nation are attending.
   Cavazos said the study is vital because the nation has no
comprehensive statistics on American Indian school achievement. But
what is known is enough to suggest that a need for extra attention,
he said.
   He noted a 90 percent unemployment rate on some Indian
reservations and a school dropout rate double the national average
of 25 percent. He said 75 percent of the American Indian students
who make it to college fail to finish.
   Cavazos titled the study ``Indian Nations at Risk,'' borrowing
from the 1983 ``A Nation at Risk'' report on the country's ailing
public education system.
</TEXT>
