<FILEID>AP-NR-10-09-89 1413EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-NATO-Woerner     10-09 0436</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-NATO-Woerner,0447</SECOND>
<HEAD>NATO Chief Calls Poland, Hungary Test Cases of NATO Strategy</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Hungary, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRY LEONARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NATO Secretary-General Manfred Woerner said Monday
the Western allies must use aid to support political change in
Poland and Hungary, which he called test cases of the alliance's
strategy.
   ``The windows have been opened in the closed societies of
Eastern Europe, the allies do not intend to let them slam shut
again,'' Woerner said in a speech to the North Atlantic Assembly, a
consultative organization of legislators from NATO countries.
   He said the flight of 50,000 East Germans to the West, the
decision to give Hungary's Communist Party a new name and platform,
strikes by Soviet miners and the ``joy of the Poles as they greet
their first non-Communist prime minister in 40 years'' demonstrate
that the peoples of the East have not become accustomed to their
political leadership.
   ``Even if the alliance does not have responsibility for specific
aid programs, only NATO can harmonize and coordinate the efforts of
the member nations as a whole on these herculean tasks; only NATO
brings the combined resources of North American and Western Europe
to bear on them,'' Woerner said.
   He said the aid efforts should concentrate on Poland and Hungary
because they are taking steps to move closer to democracy and give
reform a chance.
   ``Poland and Hungary are the two test cases,'' said Woerner.
``If reform fails, the lessons will not be lost on the hardliners
in Czechoslovakia and East Germany. But if reform succeeds, that
success will generate irresistible presures for similar change
throughout Eastern Europe.''
   He said NATO should use its limited influence to support change
by backing Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev and others in
their reforms promoting more openness, pluralism, human rights and
human contact.
   ``The postwar period has come to an end. We are seeing the
profound transformation of the European political and security
structure. This offers us opportunites which we should and will not
miss,'' said Woerner.
   But he cautioned the Western allies against making unilateral
moves that he said weaken the alliance.
   ``I will not hide my concern at a tendency that I observe today
in most of our member nations which are starting to unilaterally
reduce their defense efforts,'' said Woerner. ``It is wrong and
it's dangerous.''
   The Soviet response to allied proposals at the conventional arms
talks in Vienna has been encouraging, he said, but the Warsaw Pact
retains an overwhelming superiority in conventional arms.
   NATO must base its security on Soviet and Warsaw Pact potential,
not on announced intentions, said Woerner.
</TEXT>
