<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Etna     10-09 0163</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Etna,0169</SECOND>
<HEAD>Snow, Lava Mix on Side of Volcano</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CATANIA, Sicily (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A light snow fell on Mount Etna on Monday
as streams of fiery orange lava flowed down the side of Europe's
most active volcano.
   The lava surging from the volcano's crater and fissures had
slowed considerably from last week, said Giovanni Fazzetta of the
International Institute of Vulcanology in Catania.
   The lava was far from villages near the volcano on the southern
Italian island of Sicily, and authorities said no one was in danger.
   Earth tremors that rocked the area last week had nearly ceased,
Fazzetta said.
   Over the weekend, the flaming lava burned dozens of trees in its
path. Farmers harvested their apples early to save them from damage.
   Snow began falling Sunday evening and continued Monday morning.
   Mount Etna has been erupting since Sept. 11. While the
government has said the situation is not dangerous, it sent
prefabricated housing to the area in case evacuations become
necessary.
</TEXT>
