<FIRST>r a AM-SexAbuseLawsuits     10-09 0252</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sex Abuse Lawsuits,0257</SECOND>
<HEAD>First of Civil Lawsuits in Anneewakee Scandal Goes to Trial</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jury selection began Monday for the trial of the
first of a series of lawsuits filed by former patients who allege
they were victims of sexual abuse and battery at camps for troubled
children.
   The first lawsuit, with five plaintiffs, is being heard in
Fulton County Superior Court, where more than 100 potential jurors
were given questionnaires to fill out Monday. Attorneys estimate
the trial could take a month or longer.
   In all, eight lawsuits were filed by 120 plaintiffs who allege
they were abused while patients at Anneewakee's campuses in Douglas
County and Rockmart, Ga., and Carrabelle, Fla. The lawsuits name a
total of 31 defendants.
   The non-profit Anneewakee program, which provides long-term care
and wilderness-based therapy for teen-agers with psychological
problems, has treated hundreds of patients since it was founded 27
years ago.
   Allegations of abuse of patients surfaced in 1986.
   Anneewakee founder Louis J. Poetter, 69, pleaded guilty last
year to 19 counts of sodomy and one count of simple battery against
boys treated in the program. He was sentenced to eight years in
prison.
   In the wake of the scandal, Anneewakee was placed under the
management of the Hospital Corporation of America, with leadership
from a new board of trustees.
   Because of the number of people involved in the lawsuits, the
old Fulton County Commission meeting room in the county's
governmental complex has been pressed into service as a courtroom.
</TEXT>
