<FIRST>r i AM-Namibia     10-09 0293</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Namibia,0302</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.N. Officials Worried By Escalating Political Violence</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WINDHOEK, Namibia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   United Nations officials will urge
rival political leaders to halt ``vicious mob behavior'' by
supporters that resulted in two deaths and scores of injuries over
the weekend, a U.N. spokesman said Monday.
   The violence, which included hand grenade attacks, was the most
extensive since the campaign for next month's pre-independence
elections began in July.
   Clashes followed separate rallies held in far-northern Namibia
by the South-West Africa People's Organization and its leading
rival, the Democratic Turnhalle Alliance.
   SWAPO, favored to win the most votes in the Nov. 7-11 election,
waged a 23-year guerrilla war against South African rule of
Namibia. Its membership is overwhelmingly black and it advocates
socialist economic policies.
   The Democratic Turnhalle Alliance is multiracial, participated
in a South African-installed territorial government, and advocates
a capitalist economy.
   Fred Eckhard, spokesman for the U.N. contingent that is
overseeing the independence process, said U.N. Special
Representative Martti Ahtisaari would discuss the violence Tuesday
with leaders of the two parties.
   Ahtisaari ``was dismayed at the vicious mob behavior,'' Eckhard
said. ``He continues to monitor closely the disturbing trend in the
north.''
   Authorities said two people were killed and about 60 injured in
hand grenade attacks and clashes in and around the northern town of
Oshakati. The fighting broke out folliwng a mass rally Saturday
addressed by SWAPO President Sam Nujoma.
   South Africa has ruled Namibia since World War I, but agreed
last year to grant independence as part of a regional treaty also
calling for the withdrawal of Cuban troops from Angola, Namibia's
northern neighbor.
   The elections in November are for seats in an assembly that will
draft a constitution for an independent Namibia. No date for
independence has been set.
</TEXT>
