<FIRST>r i AM-Korea-US     10-09 0443</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Korea-US,0455</SECOND>
<HEAD>Roh Calls For Stronger Partnership With US, Scolds Dissidents</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By M.H. AHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Roh Tae-woo, who meets with
President Bush next week, said Monday he hopes for stronger ties
with the United States, and he scolded dissidents for their
anti-American attitude.
   Roh said anti-American acts such as flag-burnings and violent
protests have contributed to anti-Korean sentiments in the United
States, and he urged ``the small number of extreme radicals to
change their attitude.''
   ``I have reports that American feelings inside and outside the
government towards our country are worsening as some (South Korean)
forces have shown fierce anti-American sentiments and also
committed violent acts,'' he said in a weekly nationwide radio
address.
   Radical students and dissidents, a small but vocal minority,
have staged demonstrations demanding the withdrawal of 43,000 U.S.
troops stationed in South Korea. Radicals allege Roh is a puppet of
Washington and have called for his ouster.
   Some U.S. congressmen have proposed cutting U.S. troops strength
in South Korea, saying Seoul can afford its own defense. Bush and
Roh have said the troops would remain as long as both sides feel
they are needed.
   Roh is scheduled to visit Washington Oct. 16-18 to talk with
Bush and address a joint session of Congress on topics ranging from
bilaterial security issues to U.S. demand for a larger access to
the Korean market.
   Roh said he planned to discuss ``the direction in which our
country and the United States can advance as cooperative partners
toward common ideals.''
   Roh said trade frictions between the two countries and
controversy over the U.S. miltiary presence reflect South Korea's
growing economy and new sense of nationalism.
   South Korea's trade surplus with the United States, which buys
about 35 percent of Korea's exports, stood at $8.6 billion last
year.
   He said friction over U.S. demands for Korea to open its markets
and to appreciate its won currency against the dollar have fueled
the anti-American sentiment.
   Roh said the United States, like any other county, is seeking
its national interest. He said huge U.S. trade deficits are a
factor threatening the stability of the world economy and South
Korea's economy, heavily dependent on exports, could suffer if the
world economy falls into trouble.
   He said, however, that this does not mean South Korea should
comply with all U.S. requests in opening its markets. Washington
has threatened to retaliate if Seoul refuses to increase beef
imports and complained that Korea failed to protect American
intellectual property rights.
   He said the U.S. military presence helps maintain peace and
stability in East Asia and deters an invasion from communist North
Korea.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
