<FIRST>r a PM-JamieFiske 3rdLd-Writethru a0564 10-09 0558</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Jamie Fiske, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0564,0567</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jamie Fiske, Who Got New Liver After Public Appeals, Having Spleen
Removed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf, `Najarian said...', to restore dropped word `size.'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED STYCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Seven-year-old Jamie Fiske, who as an infant
received a liver transplant after her father's impassioned appeal
for a donor, underwent surgery today to remove her spleen.
   ``She's in the recovery room now doing very well,'' Dr. John
Najarian said after the three-hour operation at University of
Minnesota Hospital. The girl was listed in critical but stable
condition after the operation.
   Najarian said the spleen was seven or eight times normal size
for a child Jamie's age. He also said her liver ``is perfectly
normal.''
   ``Hopefully, she'll do well and be out of here in a week's
time,'' he said. ``It's hard to predict.''
   It was the first surgery for Jamie since her 1982 liver
transplant, which also took place at University of Minnesota
Hospital, said Jamie's father, Charles Fiske of Bridgewater, Mass.
At the time, she was one of the youngest liver transplant
recipients.
   Jamie was born Nov. 26, 1981, with biliary atresia, a condition
in which the liver's bile ducts are blocked. Months later, the
Fiskes learned that only a liver transplant could save her life.
   She underwent a liver transplant after her father, then a
hospital administrator, made an emotional appeal for a donor during
a convention at the American Academy of Pediatricians. The
nationally televised plea, including Fiske singing, ``Please don't
take my sunshine away,'' resulted in the offer a few days later
from a family in Utah whose 11-month-old son was killed in an
accident.
   On Saturday, Fiske said: ``We've been in worse places and
times.''
   Still, he said, ``It's major surgery for her, given the fact she
had a liver transplant. What's giving us confidence is that we're
coming back to an institution that knows her. The doctors have seen
her grow up.''
   The Minneapolis hospital sent an air ambulance Thursday to
Massachusetts to pick up Jamie and her father. Jamie, who is listed
in stable condition, has suffered three bouts of internal bleeding
this fall, and her doctors think an enlarged spleen may be
responsible, Fiske said.
   But Jamie's mind isn't on her impending surgery, Fiske said.
She's worried about whether she will be able to dress up as the
Queen of Hearts for Halloween, he said.
   ``She said to me today, `What about Halloween? Will I be back in
Boston for Halloween?'''
   He said doctors have estimated Jamie will be in the hospital for
about 10 days. Fiske said he hopes to have Jamie home in
Bridgewater, 35 miles south of Boston, by Halloween.
   Doctors don't believe Jamie's current problem is related to the
liver transplant, Fiske said in a news conference Saturday.
   Her spleen began to enlarge one year after her transplant, but
doctors said there had been no complications with it until now,
Fiske said. Her current problems began in her first week of second
grade this fall, when she suffered flu-like symptoms. She was
hospitalized for tests and doctors found she lost a large amount of
blood.
   When a spleen enlarges, blood vessels must find alternate routes
around the organ, bulge and are likely to tear. That's what doctors
believe has happened in this case, Fiske said.

</TEXT>
