<FIRST>r a AM-WifeKilling-Suicide     10-09 0367</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wife Killing-Suicide,0381</SECOND>
<HEAD>Elderly Man Charged With Killing Ailing Wife Commits Suicide</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HALLANDALE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An 80-year-old man charged with
murdering his ailing wife of 55 years killed himself a few days
before he was to face a competency hearing, officials said.
   Joseph Motchan drank a mixture of sleeping pills, alcohol and
bleach, police said, and left behind a one-sentence note that said:
``I cannot live without her.''
   A friend found his body Sunday morning.
   Motchan, of Hallandale, had survived another suicide attempt
last month. He was to face a competency hearing Tuesday before
being tried on second-degree murder charges in the July 8 slaying
of his 79-year-old wife, Gertrude.
   ``He couldn't bring her back, so he decided to join her,'' said
the friend, Dr. Reuben Kallman.
   Motchan had claimed he did not remember stabbing his wife in the
heart and beating her in the head with a hammer, as police said he
had done.
   But in a tape-recorded confession after his arrest, Motchan told
police ``Well, I murdered her.''
   ``I see these elderly people in wheelchairs,'' he added, ``and
you have to pay like four or five, six hundred dollars a week to
wheel you around, you know. You'd probably have to find cheaper
quarters or deplete the few dollars we have.''
   Motchan's wife suffered from arthritis, osteoporosis and
Alzheimer's disease, but police said she was not terminally ill.
   Motchan was released from the Broward County Jail on $25,000
bail Aug. 11.
   On Sept. 14, he took an overdose of prescription pills and was
hospitalized under a state law used to detain people for
psychological treatment if they are deemed dangerous to themselves
or others.
   But two weeks ago, doctors said he was ready to return home. And
as late as Friday, Motchan was in good spirits, said Arthur
Stillman, one of two psychiatrists who treated him.
   Motchan had only seven Valium pills left Friday, the doctor said.
   ``Seven pills, or whatever he had left after Friday, wouldn't
kill anyone,'' Stillman said. ``It couldn't even kill a child,
probably not even with the alcohol.
   ``But the Clorox, my God. That's just horrible.''
   Stillman said the bleach could burn through a victim's throat
and stomach.
</TEXT>
