<FIRST>r i AM-Nobel-France     10-09 0400</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nobel-France,0409</SECOND>
<HEAD>French Researcher Says He Should Have Been Honored</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Nobel-Medicine, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A French researcher who worked for the two
Americans honored Monday with the Nobel Prize for medicine said he
did the work on their project and should have at least shared the
award.
   ``I am very disappointed,'' said Dr. Dominique Stehelin, a
director of research for the National Center for Scientific
Research at the Pasteur Institute in Lille. ``I find all that very
unfair and rotten.''
   J. Michael Bishop and Harold E. Varmus won the Nobel Prize in
medicine for their discovery of a family of genes that has helped
scientists understand how cancer develops. Bishop and Varmus work
in the Department of Microbiology and Immunology at the University
of California School of Medicine in San Francisco.
   The 50-member Nobel Assembly of the Karolinska Institute in
Sweden cited the researchers ``for their discovery of the cellular
origin of retroviral oncogenes.''
   In 1976, Bishop and Varmus ``published the remarkable conclusion
that the oncogene in the virus did not represent a true viral gene,
but instead was a normal cellular gene,'' the citation said.
   Cancer viruses cause cancer with the help of animal genes that
have become incorporated into the viruses. The animal genes
normally help control the regular growth of cells. But when the
genes become part of viruses, they can trigger the uncontrolled
cell growth that typifies cancer tumors.
   ``I did the work all by myself, from A to Z,'' Stehelin told the
French news agency Agence France-Presse. ``I spent three years in
their San Francisco lab, from 1972 to 1975, at a time when nobody
other than me was working on the subject and I am not even
associated in this distinction (the Nobel).''
   Stehelin said he was the first and principal signer of the first
article in the scientific magazine Nature in 1976 on the discovery
of a cellular gene, which is at the origin of the emergence of a
cancer.
   ``A year after my depart from San Francisco, where I was alone,
without even a technician, two-thirds of the people in the
microbiology and immunology laboratory were working on oncogenes,''
Stehelin said.
   ``This work belongs to me,'' he said, ``and I don't know why the
scientific community refuses to attribute the discovery to me.
Undoubtedly because working in Lille is judged less prestigious
than being a researcher in San Francisco.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
