<FILEID>AP-NR-10-09-89 1535EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Poland     10-09 0560</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland,0577</SECOND>
<HEAD>Head of Solidarity Caucus Urges Faster Pace of Changes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Solidarity's parliamentary leader Monday
urged faster changes in the mass media and ``depoliticizing'' the
army and police.
   ``The state, which was monopolized by one party, now is becoming
the property of the nation,'' said Bronislaw Geremek, assessing the
record of change 100 days after the seating of the first freely
elected parliament in Poland's postwar history and the coming to
power of a Solidarity-led government last month.
   Geremek, chairman of the Citizens Parliamentary Club that
comprises 161 parliament deputies and 98 senators from Solidarity,
said that although changes enacted so far are on a ``historic
scale,'' they still are ``too little compared to what society
wants.''
   Geremek and Prime Minister Tadeusz Mazowiecki _ the East bloc's
first non-Communist government leader _ are longtime co-activists
in the Solidarity movement. But the parliamentary leader appeared
willing to criticize Mazowiecki's government in some areas.
   For instance, he said not enough changes have been made in state
television and radio. Mazowiecki's appointee to head the state
Radio-Television Committee, Andrzej Drawicz, has been on the job
for two weeks.
   ``We have the right to expect acceleration of the process ... of
making lies disappear from the radio and television screens,''
Geremek said, apparently dissatisfied that only three newscasters
prominently associated with Communist Party propaganda have been
transferred to off-screen jobs.
   Mazowiecki and Drawicz have stressed they want to avoid ``witch
hunts'' and political purges, demanding only that employees display
competence and loyalty to the new government.
   Geremek said, however, that there still needs to be a
psychological and political ``break'' in the personnel and style of
news presentation.
   He also blamed the government for ``insufficient'' information
on its decisions and explaining its decisions to the public.
   Noting that Mazowiecki had stressed the need for his government
to be led by ``truth,'' Geremek said: ``We think there is still a
lot to be done in this field.''
   Geremek said at a news conference that old habits persist within
the government apparatus ``contrary to the government's
intentions.'' He cited a recent decision to exempt collective farms
from an increase in diesel fuel prices, following the communist
tradition of giving them preferential treatment.
   ``If we don't manage to overcome the routine of the system and
those old, constantly repeated ways of governing, then even the
best programs may turn out to be impossible,'' he said.
   ``The process of freeing the system from one-party monopoly
concerns also ... the army and police,'' Geremek said.
   He noted that Defense Minister Gen. Florian Siwicki and Interior
Minister Gen. Czeslaw Kiszczak, both communists, both agreed to
``the necessity of de-politicizing'' their departments.
   ``Those two great structures of the government should be freed
from the monopoly on one party,'' said Geremek, referring to the
practice of Communist Party committees within the army and police
influencing decision-making.
   Geremek also said a public debate would be launched into whether
judges should remain members of political parties.
   He also said consultations are taking place among parliamentary
groups aimed at early passage of a constitutional amendment
removing the clause that mandates that the Communist Party have the
leading government role.
   The proposed amendment, which already is supported by Communist
Party deputies, could be taken up by the Sejm, the lower house of
parliament, Geremek said.
</TEXT>
