<FIRST>r i AM-SriLanka     10-09 0434</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sri Lanka,0449</SECOND>
<HEAD>President Invites Red Cross to Help Sri Lankan Conflict</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Ranasinghe Premadasa has
invited the Red Cross to send officials to Sri Lanka to help ease
the conflict between Sinhalese rebels and the government, an
official statement said Monday.
   A statement issued by the presidential secretariat said the Red
Cross officials will help trace missing persons, visit detention
centers and provide relief to people affected by violence.
   The invitation follows charges by human rights groups that
pro-government vigilante organizations are responsible for a wave
of killings, mostly of young Sinhalese men believed to be
sympathizers of radicals.
   The government has denied the charges and blames the radicals
for most of the 5,000 deaths reported since the Sinhalese extremist
movement began in July 1987.
   In its latest violence report Monday, the government reported 43
killings. The victims included 16 young Sinhalese men found dead in
the spot where the People's Liberation Front, a Sinhalese extremist
group, ambushed an army patrol last week.
   The government blamed ``vigilantes,'' who they said were
outraged by attacks on government troops, for the 16 killings.
   Officials also blamed vigilantes for killing three men whose
bodies were found Monday at Moratuwa, 11 miles south of Colombo.
   All 19 victims died of gunshot wounds, military officials said.
They estimated the victims' ages at between 18 and 30.
   Thirteen Sinhalese extremists were shot and killed during a
series of government operations in the past 24 hours against the
People's Liberation Front in central and southern Sri Lanka, the
government said.
   The communique, issued by the government's information
department, said large quantities or arms and ammunition were
recovered in the operations.
   Members of the Sinhalese front killed 11 civilians in the past
24 hours, the military officials said. They said most of the
victims were officials or supporters of the government.
   The front has been attacking the Sinhalese-dominated government
for two years, since the government agreed to an accord designed to
give greater autonomy to Sri Lanka's Tamil minority.
   The People's Liberation Front espouses Marxism but increasingly
has taken up a banner of ultranationalism for the Sinhalese, who
are mostly Buddhists and comprise 75 percent of the country's 16
million people.
   Tamils, who account for 18 percent of the population, are mainly
Hindus, and began fighting six years ago for an independent
homeland.
   Predominantly Hindu India, spurred by its own Tamil minority,
tried to broker an agreement to end Sinhalese-Tamil violence but
instead got bogged down in its own war with Tamil guerrillas when
it tried to disarm them.
</TEXT>
