<FIRST>u i AM-Pope     10-09 0473</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pope,0486</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pope Brings Message of Friendhsip to Most Populous Moslem Country</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Single name cq for Suharto, Sukarno</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTOR L. SIMPSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II began a visit to the
world's most populous Moslem nation Monday with a message of
friendship and assurances that his Roman Catholic flock was loyal
to Indonesia.
   In an atmosphere of controversy over a scheduled stop in East
Timor, a predominantly Catholic former Portuguese territory annexed
by Indonesia in 1976, John Paul sought to make clear that Catholics
were no threat to the archipelago's unity.
   ``I have come as a friend to all Indonesians, with a great
respect for all the people of this dynamic nation,'' he said.
   A tropical rainstorm drenched the city of nearly 8 million as
the pope arrived after a 7-hour flight from Seoul, South Korea.
John Paul knelt and kissed the wet tarmac in sticky, 90-degree heat.
   Soldiers lined the 10-mile motorcade route from the military
airport to the presidential palace, set in a ring of palm trees. He
was greeted by President Suharto, Indonesia's pro-Western leader.
   There have been reports of several threats to the pontiff's life
by Moslem extremists in this nation of 13,766 islands and about 200
ethnic and religious groups. John Paul sought to make clear that
his visit, and the 5 million Catholics among Indonesia's 157
million Moslems, pose no threat.
   During a Mass at a sports stadium built by the Soviets under
President Sukarno, who led Indonesia to independence from the
Netherlands in 1949, John Paul expressed ``cordial esteem'' to
``our Moslem brothers and sisters, who are so numerous in this
country.''
   ``I extend the hand of sincere and heartfelt friendship in our
common belief in the one God, our creator and merciful Lord,'' he
said, speaking in English.
   John Paul said Catholic Indonesians were deeply proud of their
country.
   ``We must be fully Catholic and fully Indonesian,'' he said.
``These words are deeply inscribed in the modern history of the
nation.''
   In an exchange of speeches with Suharto at an evening reception,
the pope touched lightly on the issue of human rights, stressing
that respect for individual rights is essential for the unity of a
nation.
   Suharto said, ``Men should seek to share identical things and
not to aggravate differences among them.''
   Portugal has criticized the stop in East Timor, scheduled for
Thursday, but John Paul says the visit does not imply Vatican
recognition of the Indonesian takeover.
   He told reporters on the trip from Seoul that skipping the
island would be an ``offense'' to East Timor's Catholics, who the
Vatican says number nearly 80 percent of the 690,000 people.
   The pope is scheduled to leave Indonesia on Saturday for the
island nation of Mauritius in the Indian Ocean, and return to Rome
two days later.
</TEXT>
