<FILEID>AP-NR-10-09-89 1820EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-HUD-Monticciolo     10-09 0389</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-HUD-Monticciolo,0400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Real Estate Firm With Ties to HUD Closing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A real estate investment firm will close and
absorb a $675,000 loss rather than continue an association with its
manager _ a former federal housing official linked to recent
scandals at the department, New York Newsday reported Monday.
   Eagle Capital Ltd. is shutting down, but Joseph Monticciolo,
former New York regional administrator for HUD, will go to work at
other companies of the firm's founder, the newspaper quoted Eagle's
lawyer as saying.
   ``The partners just don't want to be involved in a situation
that has attracted so much publicity,'' lawyer Arnold Biegen said.
``These people are all prominent, respected businessmen. They have
fine reputations. They want to keep them that way.''
   Monticciolo, Housing and Urban Development regional
administrator from 1981 to 1988, testified in July before a House
subcommittee investigating allegations of mismanagement and
favoritism at HUD.
   Monticciolo testified that he earmarked large sums of HUD money
for developers who later became partners at Eagle Capital. ``I made
recommendations to Washington that ultimately benefited people who
are now partners of mine,'' he said.
   Eagle Capital paid Monticciolo $125,000 a year and gave him a 15
percent interest in the firm. Closing the firm is costing the nine
investors $675,000, Biegen said.
   Monticciolo's home telephone number in Woodbury is not listed.
Telephone calls to Monticciolo's investment firm, Woodbury
Associates Inc., went unanswered Monday, Yom Kippur and the day
Columbus Day was celebrated in New York.
   Biegen was not at his law office Monday and could not be reached
at home, said Michael Shef, another lawyer in the office. Eagle
Capital had an office in Manhattan, but there was no telephone
directory listing.
   Monticciolo will be transferred to the payroll of ``shopping
center companies'' owned by Eagle founder Sheldon Goldstein, Biegen
told Newsday. The newspaper did not say what Monticciolo's new
duties will be.
   Eagle Capital is canceling six consulting contracts with
developers who deal with HUD, Biegen told Newsday.
   Newsday said six people who later became partners in Eagle
Capital were part of an investment group that bought seven
apartment buildings from HUD in 1983 for $10.9 million, putting up
only $550,000.
   Goldstein headed a small investment group that made a profit of
about $17 million in a HUD deal while Monticciolo was with HUD.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
