<FILEID>AP-NR-10-09-89 1915EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-DisappearanceTrial     10-09 0573</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Disappearance Trial,0591</SECOND>
<HEAD>Drifter Pleads Guilty, Tells Authorities Where Body is Located</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MARINETTE, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An unemployed drifter pleaded guilty
Monday to kidnapping an 11-year-old girl and told authorities he
accidentally killed her nearly 2{ years ago and buried her in
Georgia.
   The plea by Charles Blassingame, 43, averted a trial scheduled
to begin Monday, but a prosecutor said more charges are possible in
the July 1987 disappearance of Tammy Lynn Maciulis.
   District Attorney Tim Duket said he does not believe
Blassingame's account of the child's death.
   ``The prosecution reserves the right to charge him with
first-degree or second-degree murder ... if in fact he takes us to
the body and through scientific or forensic evidence it can be
proven the death was not of an accidental nature,'' Duket said.
   Lawyers said the plea agreement calls for Blassingame to serve
25 years in prison on the kidnapping charge. If the body is not
located, Blassingame has agreed to plead guilty to an extortion
charge involving an unrelated incident and will serve an additional
six years in prison.
   Circuit Judge John Hoffmann accepted the agreement but delayed
sentencing until authorities search for the body. Blassingame
agreed to accompany officials to Georgia for the search, officials
said.
   Blassingame told authorities he accidentally struck and killed
Tammy with his car, then placed her body in a duffel bag, drove to
Georgia and buried her in woods near Dalton, Ga.
   The agreement was reached during negotiations over the weekend
between the defendant, defense attorney Royce Finne, Duket and
Marinette Police Chief Patrick Ravet, who said he, Lt. Jeff Skorik,
Blassingame and Finne will fly to Georgia on Tuesday to search for
Tammy's body.
   Authorities said they consulted with Tammy's mother, Phyllis
Nicklaus, and she had no objections to the plea agreement.
   Tammy Lynn disappeared from her mother's Marinette apartment in
July 1987, touching off a nationwide search.
   Blassingame was originally charged with kidnapping, enticing a
minor for immoral purposes, and attempted second-degree sexual
assault, but the latter two counts were dropped in the plea
bargain. The attempted sex assault charge was for an incident
involving a teen-age neighbor of the Maciulis family, authorities
said.
   According to authorities, at the time of Tammy's disappearance
she and her mother and sister were living at the same apartment
complex where Blassingame was living with a woman.
   Blassingame said he was driving out of town when he discovered
Tammy in the back seat of his car.
   He said Tammy asked him to drive her to her father's home near
Chicago. Blassingame said that because he had a criminal record, he
became scared and told her to return home.
   He said that when he turned his car around, she was standing in
the way and was struck, and stopped breathing.
   Blassingame said he dumped clothing out of a duffel bag, put her
body in it and headed south.
   Finne, the defense attorney, said Blassingame's plea was
appropriate.
   ``The defendant faces strong evidence of conviction and he
legally acknowledges the strength of the state's case, but not
necessarily beyond a reasonable doubt,'' he said.
   Duket said the agreement was also in the best interest of the
state because the case was based mostly on circumstantial evidence.
   ``I am happy with the agreement. I am happy the defendant will
do a significant amount of prison time, but I am disappointed out
case wasn't strong enough to proceed to trial without any
reservations.''
</TEXT>
