<FIRST>u i AM-Poland-Walesa     10-09 0478</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-Walesa,0492</SECOND>
<HEAD>Walesa to Visit North America, Venezuela Next Month</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Solidarity leader Lech Walesa will visit
the United States, Canada and Venezuela next month and will address
a joint session of Congress on Nov. 15.
   The trip, from Nov. 12 to 20, will be his first to North America
and the longest foreign journey of his life.
   Sen. Andrzej Celinski, a Solidarity activist who returned from
the United States on Sunday after fixing Walesa's schedule, said on
Monday the 1983 Nobel laureate will meet trade union and political
leaders in all three countries.
   Walesa's visit will include a big outdoor rally at City Hall in
Chicago, a city with an ethnic Polish population second only to
Warsaw.
   Walesa, 46, leaves Poland on Nov. 11 for Toronto, where he will
meet with Polish-Canadians and trade union officials.
   He travels to Ottawa on Nov. 13 to meet with Canadian government
leaders, and arrives in Washington that evening to meet with Lane
Kirkland, president of the AFL-CIO.
   On Nov. 14, he will attend the annual AFL-CIO convention and
dine at the Capitol that evening as guest of Senate Republican
leader Robert Dole.
   Walesa addresses Congress on Nov. 15. He has said he will remind
Congress of Poland's contributions to American independence since
the Revolutionary War, and plead for U.S. support for Poland now in
its hour of need.
   Also that day, he is scheduled to receive the Robert F. Kennedy
human rights award.
   On Nov. 16, Walesa begins two days in New York. He will attend a
dinner there of the International Rescue Committee, meet with Labor
Secretary Elizabeth Dole, have talks with Jewish leaders and visit
the offices of the U.S. Polish-language daily Nowy Dziennik. On the
night of Nov. 17, he is to have dinner with one of the best-known
U.S. capitalists, publisher Malcolm Forbes.
   Walesa goes to Chicago on Nov. 18. Besides the City Hall rally,
he is to meet there with members of Congress and business leaders.
   Walesa closes out his U.S. visit on Nov. 19 with a stop in
Philadelphia, where his wife Danuta visited in July and accepted a
Freedom Prize in Walesa's name.
   Walesa travels to Caracas, Venezuela, for a meeting on Nov. 20
with the World Labor Confederation and returns to Poland the next
day.
   Walesa's stepfather lived and worked in Jersey City, N.J., until
his death, but Walesa himself has never visited the United States.
The Solidarity leader was not allowed to travel abroad for seven
years following imposition of martial law in Poland in December
1981.
   He made his first foreign trip after the martial law episode in
December 1988, when he went to France, meeting with President
Francois Mitterrand and fellow Nobel Peace laureate Andrei
Sakharov. He since has visited several European countries.
   Walesa also visited Japan in 1981.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
