<FIRST>u i AM-Nyers-Profile     10-09 0368</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nyers-Profile,0377</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nyers, Named Head of New Hungarian Party, is Veteran Politician</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Hungary, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Reszoe Nyers, who was elected Monday as
president of the new Hungarian Socialist Party, was also chairman
of the now-dissolved Communist Party and is one of the most
experienced politicians and economists in Hungary.
   ``We are breaking ... with the exercise of power along the lines
of the dictatorship of the proletariat,'' Nyers, 66, told delegates
to the congress on Sunday, a day after the new party was
established.
   A printer by trade, Nyers joined the Hungarian Social Democratic
Party early on. After the party merged with the communists in 1948,
he was a party secretary, then studied economics.
   A champion of political reform and an experienced economist who
believes in a ``socialist'' market economy, Nyers was voted into
the Politburo in May 1988.
   It was a stunning political comeback after many years in
political limbo and came as the result of a major reshuffle that
saw longtime party chief Janos Kadar ousted and replaced by Karoly
Grosz.
   ``Whoever is a reform communist or a Euro-communist and accepts
the fact that the party has to be of a socialist (nature) ... can
be a member of a new kind of Socialist Party,'' Nyers was quoted as
saying Sunday, making it clear most communists can join it.
   Nyers' history of managing economic and financial affairs dates
to 1960 when he became finance minister, a job he held until 1962.
   As a member of the party's ruling Politburo, Nyers became known
as the father of the pioneering economic reforms that gave
Hungarians the highest living standards in Eastern Europe in the
late 1960s and early 1970s.
   But in 1974, Nyers was dropped from the Politburo and stripped
of his economics post as Kadar put a brake on reforms that
apparently alarmed Leonid I. Brezhnev, who then was in power in
Moscow.
   Nyers' vast experience was the reason for his appointment last
November as special economics minister to steer Hungary through a
period of austerity.
   Now, he will have to steer the new party through a period of
political transition and help it compete in the first multiparty
elections next year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
