<FIRST>u i AM-Queen'sCousin     10-09 0517</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Queen's Cousin,0531</SECOND>
<HEAD>Queen's 21st Cousin Says She's Pregnant and Parents Cut Her Off</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 23-year-old cousin of Queen Elizabeth II says
she is pregnant and her parents cut off her funds, instructing her
to have an abortion or marry her boyfriend immediately, the
newspaper Today said Monday.
   It quoted Marina Ogilvy as saying she had written a letter to
the queen asking her to intervene with the young woman's parents,
Princess Alexandra and Sir Angus Ogilvy.
   Alexandra, sister of the Duke of Kent, is the queen's first
cousin. Marina Ogilvy is 24th in line to the throne.
   The Ogilvys issued a brief statement saying they loved their
daughter, they had not cut her off and she always was welcome at
home. A spokesman for Buckingham Palace, when asked if the royal
family would have a statement, replied: ``None whatsoever.''
   Marina Ogilvy is a pianist who won a place at London's respected
Guildhall School of Music, but recently turned it down. She worked
as a survival course instructor in 1987, once worked in the
complaints department of a London store and has a diploma in
cooking.
   She generally has avoided the public eye and made clear her
desire to live a more independent life than many royal family
members do.
   Today quoted Miss Ogilvy as saying she and her boyfriend, Paul
Mowatt, 26, want to marry after the baby is born. The newspaper did
not say when the baby was due.
   She and Mowatt live with his parents in Kingston, on the
outskirts of London.
   David Montgomery, editor of Today, said the newspaper was
contributing to the couple's daily expenses.
   He said he had ``absolutely no doubts'' about the report, which
was a rare public airing of a private royal dispute. ``I can say
100 percent that her story is true and we reported it 100 percent
accurately,'' Montgomery said.
   As quoted in Today, Miss Ogilvie said her parents stopped her
monthly allowance of $450 and denied her access to trust funds.
   She was quoted as saying that, when she asked her father, ``
`What comes first, queen and country, or your own daughter?' he
responded: `Queen and country.'''
   Today quoted her as saying she thought her parents tried to
trick her into an abortion when she went to her doctor.
   ``We are sure now that the surgery (doctor's office) tried to
fix an abortion and pretend it was a routine examination,'' Miss
Ogilvy was quoted as saying.
   According to the report, she does not dare go home because ``I
am frightened they will try and keep me there against my will.''
   About the letter to the queen, Today quoted Miss Ogilvy as
saying: ``I know she is a wise and caring woman. I just hope she
can help my parents see sense.''
   A statement issued on behalf of Princess Alexandra and her
husband said they ``are concerned at the number of inaccuracies. In
particular, they have not `cut off' their daughter. Marina is
always welcome at her home. They love her very much and feel deeply
for her at this difficult time.''
</TEXT>
