<FILEID>AP-NR-10-09-89 1748EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-IAPA     10-09 0638</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-IAPA,0660</SECOND>
<HEAD>President Pledges to End Mexican Newsprint Monopoly</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAM ROSSIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTERREY, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Carlos Salinas de Gortari
said Monday he will end a government-controlled monopoly on the
importation and sale of inexpensive newsprint in Mexico.
   The monopoly has been used in past years to retaliate against
newspapers that failed to toe the government or ruling
Institutional Revolutionary Party's line by making it difficult or
expensive for dissidents to buy newsprint elsewhere.
   ``Allow me to announce that, once we sell PIPSA, we will allow
free and total importation of newsprint, and thus avoid a monopoly
by certain groups that could affect freedom of press expression,''
Salinas told 450 members of the Inter-American Press Association
meeting in this northern Mexico city.
   Salinas was greeted with a standing ovation and shouts of
``bravo, bravo!'' when he announced the sale of Productora e
Importadora de Papel, S.A. de C.V., popularly known by its Spanish
initials of PIPSA, which is jointly owned by the government and
long-established newspapers.
   Salinas did not give any deadline for the sale in his speech at
the opening session of IAPA's 45th annual general assembly in this
Nuevo Leon state capital, about 150 miles south of Laredo, Texas.
   IAPA has about 1,300 members in the United States, Canada, Latin
America and the Caribbean.
   PIPSA was founded by President Lazaro Cardenas in 1935 when
world prices of newsprint skyrocketed and Mexican publishers were
hard pressed for money.
   It imported newsprint duty-free and distributed it among
affiliated newspapers, virtually all of which were sympathetic to
the Institutional Revolutionary Party.
   When PIPSA's charter expired in 1965, the members voted to renew
it for another 30 years.
   But Salinas has been pressing for the monopoly's dissolution
since he took office Dec. 1, as part of a campaign to cut
government subsidies and encourage competition in the free market
and greater press freedom in Mexico.
   Many established publishers said they favored continuing PIPSA
when Salinas first announced publicly that his administration was
in favor of reopening the newsprint market.
   But many more _ especially provincial newspapers _ said they
were all for it.
   ``It's a magnificent measure,'' Jose Healy, executive editor of
El Imparcial of northwestern Sonora state, said in an interview. He
said PIPSA ``has been a weapon that the government can use at any
moment.''
   Without subsidized newsprint some papers can find it difficult
to survive, especially in the saturated Mexico City market.
   In his speech, Salinas said his administration will follow a
policy of ``strict respect for freedom of expression'' and
``provide maximum security'' for Mexican journalists.
   ``A modern government accepts criticism,'' Salinas said, adding
that such criticism spurs administrations to correct or improve
their policies.
   A total of 29 Mexican journalists were slain during President
Miguel de la Madrid's six-year administration that preceded Salinas.
   Government spokesmen said most of the killings were common
crimes, involving disputes or hold-ups, but journalists have
insisted they had political motives.
   The only case brought to trial so far is that of Manuel Buendia,
a front-page columnist for the newspaper Excelsior. He was shot on
a Mexico City street in May 1984 and his assassination remained a
mystery until a federal security chief and an agent were arrested
last June.
   Prosecutors say Buendia was shot because he had uncovered a
federal security official's role in drug trafficking.
   Several others were also arrested and are on trial as
conspirators in the case, but there is continued speculation that a
coverup has concealed the roles of high-ranking de la Madrid
administration officials.
   Advances and setbacks in press freedom in Latin America were
among the major topics for discussion by the association on Monday.
   Eduardo Ulibarri, vice president of the association's Press
Freedom and Information Committee singled out Colombia and Panama
as ``the two most critical cases this year.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
