<FILEID>AP-NR-10-09-89 1922EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Hugo     10-09 0658</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hugo,0679</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soldiers Dispatched to Help Clear Hurricane Debris</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE SMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Army arrived Monday to help clear
away mountains of tinder-dry debris, damaged furniture and
destroyed appliances that litter lawns and homes devastated by
Hurricane Hugo.
   In central South Carolina, landfills are overflowing with trash
from hurricane cleanup efforts, and officials searched for
temporary dumps.
   Charleston Mayor Joseph P. Riley Jr. said he hoped much of the
debris in his city could be cleared in two weeks, but Army officers
were not as optimistic.
   ``We could have people cleaning up for the next six months,''
said Lt. Col. Jim Scott, district engineer for the Army Corps of
Engineers, which is coordinating the effort.
   No one knows how much debris may be strewn along streets and
highways, but Riley said 1,000 truck loads a day are moved out of
Charleston alone.
   About 250 engineers and soldiers from Fort Stewart, Ga., arrived
Monday equipped with 13 front-end loaders and 40 dump trucks for a
weeklong assignment. They were scheduled to hit the streets of
Charleston, Berkeley and Dorchester counties Tuesday to begin work.
   The Corps of Engineers will arrange with private contractors to
complete the cleanup.
   Last week, the same troops cleared roads in rural areas and
helped build sand dunes to protect erosion-scarred beaches along a
60-mile stretch of the coast known as the Grand Strand.
   ``These kids have been on a tour of the state nonstop,'' said
Army spokesman Capt. Mike Wilbur.
   Across South Carolina, 24 counties and 1.8 million people were
affected when Hugo rolled through the state Sept. 21, killing 18
and causing an estimated $4 billion to $5 billion in damage. In
North Carolina, Hugo killed seven people and caused an estimated
$725 million in damage.
   Brown leaves, broken limbs and logs from felled trees still line
streets and boulevards throughout the region known as the
Lowcountry. In places, branches are piled so high they block the
view of houses from the street.
   In low-lying areas and on the coastal barrier islands flooded by
the storm, damaged refrigerators, washing machines and clothes
dryers litter the landscape. In Charleston, lumber and sections of
metal roofing clutter sidewalks.
   The federal government agreed last week to pay for removing the
debris, saving state and local governments as much as $50 million.
   ``Our goal is that we would want to have and expect everything
to be picked up within two weeks,'' before cooler, dry weather
turns the debris into a fire hazard, the mayor said.
   In the inland counties of Sumter, Lee and Clarendon, landfills
near capacity before the storm are overflowing with garbage and
debris, fallen trees and food that spoiled during widespread power
outages.
   ``The county landfill ... had a thimbleful of space to begin
with,'' Lee County Administrator Barry Hickman said. ``We're in big
trouble now.''
   Tons of debris also caused problems in North Carolina. ``It's
just everywhere,'' said Al Sharp, county manager of Lincoln County,
N.C., northwest of Charlotte.
   Meanwhile, 6,048 federally supported storm cleanup jobs are
still available, said Paul Hall, the disaster coordinating officer
for the Federal Emergency Management Agency.
   Some 270,000 people lost jobs because of the storm, ``but very
few people have shown an interest in accepting those jobs,'' Hall
said. He said the positions pay more than the minimum wage, but he
did not know how much.
   Sam Pike, director of the state Employment and Security
Commission's Charleston office, said he believed hurricane victims
are still more concerned with securing electricity, food and
housing than with temporary jobs.
   The American Red Cross announced that only two emergency
shelters housing 199 people remained in operation in South
Carolina. At one point, 453 shelters housed 87,230 people in North
Carolina, South Carolina, Georgia and Tennessee.
   The number of meals the agency is serving has also dropped. On
Sunday, 9,216 meals were served, down from 13,909 meals served
Saturday, spokeswoman Georgeanne McDaniel said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
