<FIRST>r a AM-Obit-Lernoux     10-09 0369</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Lernoux,0380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Journalist, Author Dies of Cancer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OSSINING, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Penny Lernoux, a prize-winning journalist
and author noted for books on the role of the Catholic Church in
Latin America, has died. She was 49.
   Ms. Lernoux died of cancer Sunday at Northern Westchester
Hospital Center in Mount Kisco, according to Sister Elizabeth Roach
of the Maryknoll Sisters.
   Ms. Lernoux had lived in South America since 1962, the past 20
years in Bogota, Colombia. Recently, she had been staying at the
convent, working on a book about the Maryknoll Sisters.
   Her 1980 book, ``Cry of the People,'' received acclaim for its
depiction of the struggle for human rights in Latin America and the
church's involvement.
   Ms. Lernoux, a graduate of the University of Southern
California, worked for the Copley News Service from 1964 through
1976 in Caracas, Venezuela, Buenos Aires and Bogota.
   Since 1976, she worked as a free-lance writer. ``Cry of the
People'' received Columbia University's Maria Moors Cabot award and
the Sidney Hillman Foundation Book Award.
   This year, she published ``People of God: The Struggle for World
Catholicism,'' which criticized the Vatican and praised the
emergence of a ``new kind of church'' that is sensitive to the
millions of poor Catholics in Latin America.
   ``As a Catholic observer who has lived in the Third World for
nearly 30 years,'' she wrote, ``I have followed developments in the
church, at times in despair but mostly with optimism.
   ``The hope that a new church of the poor has given to the
impoverished masses of Latin America is, in my opinion, the most
significant political development in the region in recent decades.
That church has also given me new faith.''
   Among the awards she received were two citations from the
Overseas Press Club of America, in 1969 and 1970, and the Tom
Wallace Inter-American Press Association award in 1973. She also
wrote for Harper's, The Nation and the National Catholic Reporter.
   She is survived by her husband, Denis Nahum, and their daughter,
Angela, both of Bogota; her parents, Beatrice Campeau Lernoux and
Maurice Lernoux of Hemet, Calif.; and a sister, Lisa Lernoux of San
Diego.
   A funeral Mass was scheduled Wednesday, at the Maryknoll Sisters
Center in Ossining.
</TEXT>
