<FILEID>AP-NR-10-09-89 1848EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-UN-Namibia     10-09 0558</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UN-Namibia,0573</SECOND>
<HEAD>UN Says Namibian Police Not Cooperating Fully with Monitors</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Namibian police withhold information and
deny U.N. officials the right to visit people in detention,
Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar said Monday in a report
to the Security Council.
   He also said the South-West African police force, known as
SWAPOL, was delaying investigations.
   ``In many cases they have proceeded very slowly and there is a
risk that some of them, including some serious cases of homicide,
will not be completed within the transition period, with the result
that important and crucial evidence may thus be lost,'' he said.
   About 1,000 U.N. police monitors are in Namibia and 500 more are
being sent to supervise SWAPOL, trained by South Africa, during a
one-year period in which the territory is to gain independence.
   The foreign ministers of Burundi, Uganda and Mali spoke out
against South Africa on Monday, the beginning of the third week of
General Assembly debate.
   Foreign Minister Cyprien Mbonimpa of Burundi said free elections
scheduled for November in Namibia give hope the General Assembly
can welcome it as an independent nation next year. Namibians are to
choose an assembly to write a constitution and organize the first
independent government in the territory of 1.3 million people.
   Paul Kawanga Ssemogerere of Uganda said elements of the Namibian
police ``and other South African agents'' threaten the South-West
Africa People's Organization, the Namibian nationalist party known
as SWAPO.
   Anton Lubowski, SWAPO's legal advisor, was assassinated outside
his Windhoek residence in September and an Irishman who entered the
territory from South Africa has been detained.
   N'golo Traore, foreign minister of Mali, said Lubowski's death
was the result of ``sordid plots'' by South African racists.
   Perez de Cuellar's report said there was no arrangement for U.N.
monitors to visit detainees at police stations and monitors were
not allowed to attend interrogations of SWAPOL members accused of
offenses.
   ``On occasion,'' SWAPOL has failed to inform U.N. monitors of
its schedule of patrols, making it difficult for supervisors from
the U.N. Transition Assistance Group (UNTAG) to accompany them, the
report said.
   The secretary-general added: ``Nor has SWAPOL always shared with
UNTAG information relevant to the security situation in Namibia,
though it has often made unsubstantiated allegations of imminent
infiltration by SWAPO combatants from southern Angola.''
   SWAPO, a guerrilla group as well as a political party, has
fought South African occupation of Namibia since 1966.
   More than 1,000 SWAPO fighters crossed into northern Namibia
from Angola on April 1, prompting days of skirmishes with Namibian
police and South African troops. Hundreds of guerrillas and dozens
of soldiers and police were reported killed.
   On two occasions since, South Africa has raised false alarms of
impending SWAPO invasions.
   ``It is clearly important that security information should be
shared with UNTAG, in order to prevent any recurrence of disturbing
terrorist incidents which have taken place in recent weeks,
including a murderous attack on UNTAG locations at Outjo on Aug. 10
and the assassination of a leading official of SWAPO in Windhoek
(Lubowski) on Sept. 12,'' Perez de Cuellar reported.
   He said he had increased the number of police monitors from 500
to 1,500 since April ``in order to deal with complaints received
from Namibians who do not wish to address themselves directly'' to
the police.
</TEXT>
