<SECOND>AM-Atrium Accident,0249</SECOND>
<HEAD>Worker Falls 12 Stories, Strikes Man on Way Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN ANTONIO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An electrician repairing a sign on the roof
of a medical office building fell 12 stories Monday, crashing
through a skylight and hitting a person before landing on a table
in a coffee shop.
   ``There were some ladies screaming downstairs pretty bad,'' said
Oscar Gallegos, who works in the building and saw the fall. ``It
was chaotic. There were people all over. There were doctors and
nurses all over.''
   Electrician Troy Livingston was in critical condition at St.
Luke's Lutheran Hospital and the person he struck, who was not
identified, was in guarded condition, hospital spokesman Walter
Baker said.
   Livingston and another electrician had just finished fixing an
electric sign on the building's roof when he fell, tumbling eight
stories outside before crashing through an atrium skylight on the
fourth floor, police Sgt. Pat Kilough said.
   The skylight was above an enclosed courtyard area of the
building that extended from the fourth floor to the first floor.
   The person Livingston struck was sitting on a bench on the
second floor, waiting for X-rays. After Livingston struck the
person, Livingston landed on a table in the first-floor coffee shop.
   There were people in the coffee shop, but no one was injured,
police said.
   Livingston, employed by Outdoor Lighting Services, is in his
20s, but company spokesman Rick Garcia said he did not know his
exact age.
