<FIRST>r i AM-Chile-Army     10-09 0218</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chile-Army,0223</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pinochet Retires Deputy Army Commander, 11 Other Generals</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Augusto Pinochet reduced the
number of army generals by five Monday, two months before elections
for a civilian government to replace his military regime.
   He retired 12 generals, including deputy army commander Jorge
Zincke, and promoted seven officers to general rank. Chosen to
replace Zincke was Gen. Jorge Lucar Figueroa, now barracks
commander for Santiago, the capital.
   Gen. Pinochet's changes were part of an annual restructuring of
the army leadership.
   Since losing a referendum Oct. 5, 1988, on extending his rule to
1997, Pinochet has reduced the number of generals from 56 to 43.
Pinochet has been army commander since shortly before the uprising
in September 1973 that ousted President Salvador Allende, an avowed
Marxist who died in the coup.
   The referendum defeat obliged Pinochet to schedule the December
elections for a civilian government to be inaugurated March 11.
   Reduction in the number of top officers appears designed to help
ease the military's departure from major government posts and its
return to the barracks.
   Pinochet, 73, has said he will remain as army commander under
the new government. The 1980 constitution, written by his
administration, allows him and the navy, air force and national
police commanders to keep their jobs until 1998.
  
