<FIRST>r a AM-WeatherpageWeather     10-09 0283</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0290</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cold Over The Upper Great Lakes And Ohio Valley</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Unseasonably low temperatures chilled the upper Great Lakes
states and much of the lower Ohio Valley on Monday, breaking 13
low-temperature records for the date and tying one.
   The low of 28 at Detroit erased a record on the books since 1876
and the low of 30 at Dayton, Ohio, toppled a mark that had stood
since 1889. Indianapolis' low of 30 tied the record set 1876.
   Other records were 25 at Flint, Mich.; 26 at Fort Wayne, Ind.;
23 at Grand Rapids, Mich.; 35 at Greer, S.C.; 23 at Jackson, Mich.;
23 at Lansing, Mich.; 29 at Mansfield, Ohio; 20 at Marquette,
Mich.; 27 at South Bend, Ind.; 25 at Toledo, Ohio, and 25 at
Traverse City, Mich.
   Monday's lowest reading for the Lower 48 states was 15 at
Gunnison, Colo.
   Warnings for frost or freezing temperatures were posted
overnight into Tuesday morning over sections of inland southeastern
New York state, the mountains of western Pennsylvania, southern
Maryland, much of inland Virginia, the District of Columbia area,
southeastern West Virginia, much of western and northern North
Carolina, and the mountains of South Carolina.
   Tuesday morning in the mountains of northern Georgia was
expected to be the coldest so far this season.
   Showers were scattered over the southern half of the Florida
Peninsula, light rain was scattered over central New York state,
and showers reached from central Minnesota into northwestern
Wisconsin.
   However, no significant rainfall was reported during the six
hours up to 2 p.m. EDT.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 34 at
Hibbing, Minn., to 102 at Palm Springs, Calif.
</TEXT>
