<FIRST>u i AM-Poland-Refugees 1stLd-Writethru a0596 10-09 0506</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-Refugees, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0596,0517</SECOND>
<HEAD>Solidarity Newspaper Reports Refugees Returned Against Will</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with new figures on number of refugees, quote
from Polish Red Cross; CORRECTS Szczecin location to northwestern Poland.
No pickup</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-East Germany, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four East German refugees were sent home
after they entered Poland, a pro-Solidarity newspaper said Monday.
An Interior Ministry spokesman said he could not confirm the report.
   The number of refugees registered with the West German Embassy
in Warsaw reached about 500 on Monday, the official news agency PAP
reported.
   If the report on the deportations was true, it would seem to
violate assurances reportedly given West Germany by the
non-Communist foreign minister, Krzysztof Skubiszewski, that no
East German on Polish territory would be sent home against his will.
   Henryk Wozniakowski, deputy government spokesman, said it
appeared such incidents had occurred. He said the matter was being
brought to the attention of Prime Minister Tadeusz Mazowiecki.
   Wozniakowski said returning refugees to East Germany could be
justified on purely legal grounds, but he expected Mazowiecki would
take a ``human rights'' approach.
   Gazeta Wyborcza, the pro-Solidarity paper, said the four East
Germans were asked for their documents at Szczecin in northwestern
Poland, and were sent back when they could not produce the exit
permits issued by East German authorities to legal travelers to
Poland.
   Interior Ministry spokesman Andrzej Sadlinski said Monday that,
as far as he knew, border troops returned to East Germany only
those people apprehended in the border zone while still trying to
enter Poland.
   Asked about the Gazeta Wyborcza report, he said: ``I personally
have not heard of such incidents.''
   Solidarity parliamentary leader Bronislaw Geremek, asked if
Poland should give a right of asylum to all East Germans fleeing
their country, said ``the same values and freedoms we fight for
should be present in Polish foreign policy.''
   Geremek said he supported the previously employed solution to
the question of refugees in Poland. Two East German trains carrying
more than 1,400 refugees were allowed to leave Poland last week for
West Germany.
   ``Human rights and international conventions'' governing free
movement of refugees should be the first consideration, Geremek
said.
   Since the last train left Thursday night, up to 400 new refugees
have reached the West German Embassy in Poland, including about 40
new arrivals Monday.
   Roman Catholic church groups, charitable organizations and the
Polish Red Cross are helping care for the refugees, PAP reported.
   ``By providing accomodation, food and clothers, if needed, we
are granting strictly humanitarian aid,'' the Red Cross general
secretary, Izabela Gutfeter, told the agency. She said it was
cooperating with the West German Red Cross.
   Government spokeswoman Malgorzata Niezabitowska said Friday that
407 East Germans trying to enter Poland illegally were turned back
at the border by Polish border guards.
   Unlike Czechoslovakia, Poland has not demanded that the East
Germans in Warsaw remain on West German embassy grounds. It even
has helped shelter them in vacation hotels on the outskirts of
Warsaw.
</TEXT>
