<FIRST>r i AM-SolidarityShip     10-09 0168</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Solidarity Ship,0172</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Company Names Ship for Solidarity Trade Union</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Solidarity's shipyard workers have built
lots of vessels over the years, but they finally will have one they
can call their own.
   The state Polish Shipping Co. announced Monday it plans to name
a ship under construction ``Solidarnosc'' in honor of the formerly
banned trade union led by Lech Walesa that won legal status again
this year, the state PAP news agency said.
   The ship is scheduled to be completed by December 1991, said the
shipping monopoly, based in Szczecin.
   The proposal for the name came from Solidarity members at the
shipping company, PAP said.
   Union members first applied to name a ship Solidarnosc in
December 1980. But ``due to developments in December 1981, the idea
did not come off,'' said PAP in reference to the imposition of
martial law and subsequent ban on Solidarity.
   Solidarity was legalized again in April and Poland's new prime
minister, Tadeusz Mazowiecki, is a Solidarity activist.
</TEXT>
