<FIRST>r a AM-FloridaAbortion     10-09 0435</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Florida Abortion,0447</SECOND>
<HEAD>Martinez Refuses To Concede Defeat On Eve Of Session</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Abortionist Legislator Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JACKIE HALLIFAX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Bob Martinez refused to concede
defeat Monday on the eve of the nation's first legislative action
on abortion since a U.S. Supreme Court decision, despite
predictions that nothing will be done.
   ``I do believe that the debate has already caused victory in my
mind in the sense that we're now looking at it (the fetus) as part
of the human race,'' Martinez told reporters as a few anti-abortion
pickets walked outside the Capitol.
   The governor called a special session beginning Tuesday to
consider restrictions on abortions as a result of the U.S. Supreme
Court's July 3 ruling upholding Missouri state restrictions on
abortions.
   Thousands of activists on both sides of the issue flocked to the
city for the session, and security was tight Monday.
   Martinez's proposals include requiring viability tests if women
20 weeks pregnant seek abortions; banning the use of public
recources for abortions; expanding the regulations abortion clinics
must abide by and requiring physicians to tell women seeking
abortions about the development of their fetuses.
   Legislative leaders have said all summer that there's little
chance of any of the governor's objectives making it through
committees. And the anti-abortion movement suffered a defeat last
week when the state Supreme Court struck down a 1988 parental
consent law, ruling it violated a privacy clause in the state
Constitution.
   The heads of key committees have said new abortion regulations
would not make it to the floor.
   Senate President Bob Crawford said he had assured anti-abortion
forces only that proposals for greater regulations would get a fair
hearing, not that they would go to the floor.
   A couple of lawmakers have had body guards assigned to them,
according to Crawford.
   Earlier Monday, a national pro-choice official accused Martinez
of ``playing politics'' with women's lives.
   ``Tomorrow will be judgment day in Tallahassee,'' said Kate
Michelman, executive director of the National Abortion Rights
Action League. ``What happens here will resonate in every corner of
this nation.''
   ``For Governor Martinez, this special session will be a crashing
disappointment and a major political embarrassment,'' Ms. Michelman
said in an address to the Florida Abortion Council.
   Her comments were echoed at a news conference later by Patricia
Ireland, executive vice president of the National Organization for
Women, and Eleanor Smeal, president of the Feminist Majority. They
called the legislative an exercise in futility.
   Smeal criticized Martinez, a Roman Catholic, for attempting to
impose his religious views on abortion on the rest of the state.
</TEXT>
