<FIRST>r a AM-MedievalRuckus     10-09 0312</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Medieval Ruckus,0324</SECOND>
<HEAD>Protesters Get Their Way: No More `Evil' in Medieval Festival</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SARATOGA SPRINGS, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A local charitable organization
canceled plans Monday to hold a medieval festival after
fundamentalist Christians protested the ``evil'' implications of
the Friday the 13th event.
   ``For the greater good we thought we would just accommodate
them,'' said William Doyle, an organization volunteer for the
Saratoga Springs chapter of the American Cancer Society.
   The festival, originally intended to feature tarot card and
astrology readings, was changed to a general costume ball.
   ``It's crazy,'' said psychic Ann Fisher, the fair's honorary
chairwoman. ``It's a misinterpretation of the period of history.
We're just trying to do something good. It's a fund-raiser.''
   But protesters said they found more than the date and its
featured events ominous, claiming mystic references in fliers
advertising the festival.
   ``Tarot card readings or fortune-telling or things like that
would bring in spiritual forces that are very dangerous,'' said
Rev. Eric Walton, pastor of the Clifton Park Center Baptist Church,
about 20 miles north of Albany.
   Members of the church also protested such things as Life
magazine's cover featuring a woman wearing a bra.
   Doyle said some protesters also objected to the word medieval,
believing its ending sounded ``evil.''
   The idea of the fair was objectionable, not just the scheduled
events, said Paul Lincoln, chairman of the board of Maranatha
Baptist Church in nearby Ballston Spa.
   ``It sure would, because of the evil spirits. You're getting
into the spirit realm and the devil,'' he said. ``We're certainly
against it.''
   Doyle said he was not sure why the protesters had singled out
Friday's function since similar events held in the area had not
been targeted in the past.
   Pat Brown, organizer of the Medieval Faire at the Cathedral of
All Saints in Albany, also set for Friday, said her organization
had heard no protests.
</TEXT>
