<FILEID>AP-NR-10-09-89 2031EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Greece     10-09 0302</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Greece,0311</SECOND>
<HEAD>Papandreou Fails in Bid to Form Greek Government</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PHILIP DOPOULOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Premier Andreas Papandreou failed
Monday to persuade other leftist forces to join his socialist camp
in a coalition government.
   The collapse of that effort means Greeks face new general
elections in November, only five months after the last voting.
   Papandreou told President Christos Sartzetakis on Monday he had
failed in his three-day presidential mandate for form a new
government.
   Emerging from the presidential palace in Athens, the 70-year-old
Papandreou told reporters he outlined proposals of his Panhellenic
Socialist Movement in a memorandum to the president. However, he
did not elaborate.
   Later in the day, Communist Party chief Harilaos Florakis was
summoned to the presidential palace, but he declined to try to put
together a government.
   The political crisis stems from the elections June 18, when no
party won a majority in parliament. Conservatives and leftists
banded together in an unusual alliance to press forward legal
action against socialist officials accused of corruption, including
Papandreou himself.
   However, the alliance said it would govern only temporarily, and
its government stepped down after three months. Conservative New
Democracy Party leader Constantine Mitsotakis has agreed to remain
caretaker until a new government is formed.
   He too has rejected a presidential mandate to try to form a
government, saying he wanted to ``quickly clear any obstacles to
elections'' on Nov. 5.
   Parliament has accused Papandreou of corruption in connection
with a $210 million embezzlement scandal at the Bank of Crete and
with purported wiretapping of political friends and enemies.
   Lawmakers last month sent Papandreou's case to special courts.
They are scheduled to convene within 60 days to try him along with
several ex-ministers.
   If found guilty, Papandreou could receive up to 20 years in
prison.
</TEXT>
