<FIRST>u i BC-Britain-Chess     10-09 0248</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Britain-Chess,0255</SECOND>
<HEAD>Timman Holds Draw in Resumed Fourth Game; Leads Speelman 3-2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GOODMAN</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jan Timman of the Netherlands drew a marathon
116-move battle with Jon Speelman of England in the resumed fourth
round game of the World Chess Championship Candidate semifinal
Monday to retain his one point lead.
   The two had played the fifth game of eight on Sunday and Timman
now leads 3-2. A win scores one point and a draw a half.
   Play was adjourned after six hours play Saturday night when
Speelman sealed his 64th move in a position well known as a
technical draw, but where Speelman could test Timman's defensive
technique for many moves.
   But Timman, well-primed after overnight analysis of the
position, rattled off his moves on Monday until Speelman gave up
and offered a draw on the 116th move.
   The winner of the Candidates' cycle will challenge world
champion Garri Kasparov for his title in a 24-game contest
beginning in October 1990. The winning semifinalists will face off
in the Candidates' final next March.
   In the other semifinal, former world champion Anatoly Karpov
leads fellow Soviet Artur Yusupov 2.5-1.5 after four games.
   The Soviets are one game behind because Yusupov took a timeout
on Sunday postponing his fifth game with Karpov until Tuesday.
   The sixth game between Speelman and Timman is also scheduled for
Tuesday.
   If either match ends in a 4-4 tie, two further games will be
played, followed if necessary by sudden-death tiebreakers.
</TEXT>
