<FIRST>r i AM-Peru     10-09 0213</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Peru,0221</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rebels Kill Candidate's Driver, Kidnap Rancher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leftist guerrillas killed a political
candidate's driver Monday and insurgents from another group
kidnapped a rancher in the country's latest outbreak of rebel
attacks, authorities said.
   Police said three Maoist Shining Path rebels killed the
chauffeur of the mayoral candidate Monday in Concepcion, 120 miles
east of Lima.
   They said the candidate, Richard Muller of the center-right
Fredemo Party, was not in his car when the rebels sprayed it with
gunfire. A bodyguard was also wounded, authorities said.
   Shining Path rebels have assassinated 50 mayors the past five
years. They are now seeking to disrupt municipal elections
scheduled for Nov. 12.
   The group began its armed insurgency against Peru's elected
government in 1980.
   Authorities also said rebels of the pro-Cuban Tupac Amaru
Revolutionary Movement kidnapped rancher Oswaldo Zender from his
home after setting fire to the Iscozasin town hall, about 140 miles
northeast of Lima.
   The rebels left a note for Zender's family demanding $100,000 in
ransom.
   The Tupac Amaru group operates separately from the Shining Path.
It took up arms in 1984 and has mostly engaged in urban attacks
against government and business targets.
   The government says more than 15,000 people have died during
nine years of rebel violence.
</TEXT>
