<SECOND>AM-Philippines-Typhoon,0150</SECOND>
<HEAD>45 Reported Dead, 50 Missing From Typhoon Angela</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Floods from Typhoon Angela drowned at
least 45 people and left 50 others missing in coastal villages
north of Manila, officials said Monday.
   The Red Cross and the Office of Civil Defense said the
casualties occurred last week in Gonzaga, 250 miles north of
Manila, and nearby Santa Ana.
   Twenty-six drowned in Gonzaga and 19 in Santa Ana, officials
said. The 50 missing were scattered in communities along the
northern coast of Luzon, the main Philippine island.
   Casualty reports from typhoons often take days to reach Manila
because of the country's poor communications system.
   Typhoon Angela swept across the mountainous northern coast
Friday with winds up to 108 mph before entering the South China Sea.
   On Monday, the storm was reported to be in the Paracel islands
headed toward Vietnam.
