<FIRST>r a AM-HomelessDefenders     10-09 0275</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Homeless Defenders,0281</SECOND>
<HEAD>Public Defenders Lose Office to Rats, Still Homeless Months Later</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAGUNA NIGUEL, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stench of rotting rats drove a
group of public defenders from their office trailer in February and
they're still homeless because no one will rent them space.
   The attorneys say landlords near South Orange County Municipal
Court don't want them as tenants because they don't want a steady
stream of criminal defendants in their buildings.
   ``Most of the people seem to have the idea that with us come the
riffraff of Orange County. That's just not the case,'' said Bob
Goss, the senior deputy public defender who shut down the old
offices because of the stink.
   The court's presiding judge, Pamela Iles, said the public
defenders' clientele is by and large not dangerous.
   ``They are indigent and they deserve attorneys just like people
with money,'' she said.
   The defenders represent 350 people a month. They have long
needed more space, but the crunch became a crisis when a county
pest extermination effort left the old trailer's walls and floors
filled with decaying rat remains.
   For the time being, the defenders work out of a tiny temporary
trailer and a meeting room at a library down the hill from the
court. Files and law books are stored at the courthouse.
   ``At this point the rats are starting to look good,'' said Carl
Holmes, the county's chief deputy public defender.
   The solution appears to be a plan to add a two-story building at
South Court. Susan Novak, an analyst for the county administrative
office, will pitch the idea to the county Board of Supervisors in
several weeks.
</TEXT>
