<FIRST>u i AM-Colombia     10-09 0529</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Colombia,0546</SECOND>
<HEAD>Furor in Colombia Over Reports President Contacted Drug Cartels</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STAN YARBRO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Colombia was in an uproar Monday over
whether President Virgilio Barco explored a possible truce with the
cocaine cartels, even as new raids were reported in Barco's
declared war on drug traffickers.
   Authorities raided five cocaine laboratories along the Rosario
River in southwestern Narino state, arrested eight people and
destroyed a ton of coca leaves used to make the drug, the national
radio chain Caracol reported, citing the commander of the state's
antinarcotics police as its source.
   Police also reportedly seized weapons as well as coca seeds and
chemicals used in processing cocaine.
   With the president's credibility at stake in his war on drugs,
former Interior Minister Joaquin Vallejo confirmed in published
reports Sunday that he acted as a go-between in truce negotiations
between the Medellin cartel and Barco's government.
   The Bogota daily La Prensa on Saturday revealed Vallejo's role
in the alleged negotiations and the 76-year-old Vallejo confirmed
that role in interviews published Sunday by Bogota newspapers El
Tiempo and El Espectador.
   Vallejo reportedly said there were never any direct negotiations
and the subject was approached only through intermediaries.
   He was quoted as saying the government did not discourage the
contacts that started in September 1988 and ended almost a year
later.
   The contact roles were played by a Medellin lawyer representing
the traffickers; Vallejo as the messenger; and Barco's general
secretary, German Montoya, who fielded the messages, Vallejo was
quoted as saying.
   Montoya had said such negotiations would be possible only if the
United States and other cocaine-consuming countries agreed to
participate, the papers quoted Vallejo as saying.
   They quoted Vallejo as saying the U.S. government's strong
opposition to any dealings with the drug lords made direct
negotiations impossible.
   ``Since the program of President Bush has been to fight drugs
militarily, the Colombian government had big problems convincing
the administration to accept the arrangement,'' Vallejo said,
according to El Tiempo.
   ``This is going to generate a huge national debate,'' El
Espectador quoted Fabio Valencia, an opposition Conservative Party
senator, as saying. ``It seems to me that the government continues
to handle matters with a double morality.''
   Montoya said in a communique Saturday night that he had not
negotiated with traffickers and vehemently denied the La Prensa
account. He said his decision to meet with Vallejo was a personal
one and that he told Vallejo negotiations with the drug traffickers
was not possible.
   Memos and other documents about the purported contacts were
delivered to La Prensa by Alvaro Leyva, a Conservative Party
senator.
   He was quoted as saying in an interview published Sunday in El
Espectador that he wondered if the Barco administration ``tricked
everyone'' by negotiating with traffickers while maintaining a
hard-line public stance against them.
   Barco unleashed a campaign against traffickers Aug. 19, one day
after Sen. Luis Carlos Galan, a leading presidential candidate, was
killed, ostensibly by hitmen hired by drug traffickers.
   Barco has said repeatedly since the crackdown began that he will
never negotiate with the drug lords.
   Traffickers reacted to the government declaration of war against
them with a bombing campaign.
</TEXT>
