<FIRST>u a AM-SalemBombs 2ndLd-Writethru a0670 10-09 0534</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Salem Bombs, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0670,0546</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jury Convicts Man in Bombings</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 10 grafs to UPDATE with Hubbard's comments, no sentencing
date set, Hubbard in custody. Picks up 5th graf, `In closing...'.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBBIE NEWBY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ALBANY, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal jury Monday convicted a man on
19 counts for the planting of 13 bombs in nearby Salem, a plot
prosecutors said was rooted in his lifelong rivalry with a state
legislator.
   The U.S. District Court jury deliberated just over three hours
before returning the guilty verdicts against John M. Hubbard III.
   Hubbard's attorney, Paul J. Watts, unexpectedly rested his case
Monday afternoon without calling witnesses.
   Hubbard, 32, of Salem, was charged with 29 counts including
conspiracy, illegal possession of dynamite, 14 counts of making
bombs and 13 counts of attempting to destroy bridges and buildings
used in interstate commerce. No bombs actually exploded.
   Hubbard began to weep before the jury returned to the courtroom
and his family members cried as the verdicts were announced.
   ``We love you and still believe in you,'' Hubbard's mother, Opal
Kramer, told her son as he was led out of the courtroom.
   Hubbard turned to her and said, ``Let the world know.''
   On his way out of the courthouse, Hubbard told reporters, ``I
know I'm innocent; God knows I'm innocent.''
   Watts said he was not certain whether the case will be appealed.
No sentencing date was set. Hubbard has been in custody since his
arrest in May.
   Jerry Conrad, 42, one of Hubbard's co-workers at a Salem
factory, was convicted on all 29 counts following a trial last
month. Salem in in south-central Indiana, about 30 miles northwest
of Louisville.
   In closing arguments Monday, Assistant U.S. Attorney Robert
Stanley Powell described Hubbard as a ``guerrilla fighter in his
own mind.''
   ``He wanted the thrill of being able to see the fear and the
panic on people's faces about the bombs and the chaos he had
created in Salem,'' said Powell.
   Powell said Hubbard was motivated by his lifelong rivalry and
hatred for state Rep. Frank Newkirk Jr, a Democrat from Salem. ``He
resented him for a lifetime of accomplishments that he thought
Frank Newkirk Jr. had that Mr. Hubbard didn't,'' Powell said.
   But Watts contended it was absurd to suggest Hubbard would plant
a bomb within 150 feet of his own house and then return home to his
wife and children to ``wait to be blown off the face of the earth
because he didn't get a part in a school play in high school.''
   Watts said the government's case was based entirely on
circumstantial evidence, much of it provided by ``purchased
testimony.''
   Government witnesses included a paid informant, who was a
convicted felon, and an inmate who met Hubbard when both were at
the Marion County Jail.
   Watts told jurors Hubbard had continued to deny involvement in
the bomb case. He characterized any boastful statements Hubbard
made as ``the meanderings of a drunk. That's pretty clear.''
   The defense attorney described Hubbard as a ``gun nut who loads
his own ammunition, who has weird politics. We know he exaggerates;
we know that when he's drunk, he lies,'' Watts said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
