<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Senate stalemate that centers on President
Bush's capital gains cut is taking on a new wrinkle as liberal
Democrats seek to ensure expansion of tax credits for low-income
working parents.
   Leaders face an Oct. 16 deadline as they try to negotiate their
way out of the hangup. Unless Congress completes work by then on a
deficit-reduction plan of spending cuts and tax increases,
automatic across-the-board reductions will be triggered in most
federal spending programs.
   Senate Democratic and Republican leaders spent all of Saturday
and half of Sunday looking for a solution. They agreed only to
resume their efforts Tuesday.
   ``We don't have an agreement yet but everybody in there today
thought we should get one,'' Senate Republican Leader Bob Dole of
