<FIRST>a i PM-Japan-BorrowedWords Adv16   10-09 0636</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Borrowed Words, Adv 16,0655</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv16</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Mon PMs Oct. 16 or Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Japanese Ministry Puts Brakes on Borrowing Words from English</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY THORSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Among the world's languages, Japanese is one of the
most eager borrowers of foreign words. But one arm of the
bureaucracy is putting on the brakes. Very gently.
   Please, not ``konseputo'' _ how the Japanese pronounce
``concept.'' Use ``kihonteki kangaekata'' (basic idea) instead.
   And no more ``masuta puran'' (master plan), says the Ministry of
Health and Welfare. Let's say ``kihon keikaku'' (basic plan) and
more Japanese people will understand.
   But the ministry's list of English words to be avoided in
official documents is accompanied by a list of acceptable ones.
   It wouldn't do in France, where the Commissariat General de la
Langue Francaise battles against the ``Franglais'' that results
from unapproved cohabitation with English.
   If the commissariat ordered ``un bulldozer'' to be pushed aside
for ``bouteur,'' the French certainly would never agree with the
Japanese ministry's acceptance of ``homu herupa'' for ``home
helper'' _ people who help the elderly at home. The Japanese, by
the way, would translate the French word ``bouteur'' as
``burudoza.''
   The Ministry of Health and Welfare issued guidelines on foreign
words this past summer because Junichiro Koizumi, the minister at
the time, felt that many ordinary people would not understand some
of the foreign words used in the ministry's jargon, said Masato
Shibata, a senior planning officer.
   The ministry wants to help people, but ``if they don't
understand what we're saying, then they don't get help,'' Shibata
said.
   Borrowed words are written in the katakana script, one of three
scripts in the complex Japanese writing system. Used like italics,
katakana is an angular script in which each symbol is a syllable. A
rounded-looking script called hiragana also uses a symbol for each
syllable.
   Though every Japanese word could be written in those two
scripts, there is also kanji, or Chinese-style characters. One must
know 2,000 or so kanji to be able to read a Japanese newspaper,
while the katakana and hiragana scripts have about 50 symbols each.
   In contrast to its wildly rich writing system, spoken Japanese
has fewer sounds than English and European languages _ no L, no TH,
no V, a weak F, a low number of consonant combinations. So foreign
words often are barely recognizable when adopted into Japanese.
``Needs,'' for instance, is one of the words rejected by the
Ministry of Health. It is written in katakana as either ``needo''
or ``neezu.'' Suggested alternatives are juyo (demand) and yobo
(request).
   But Japanese people have been borrowing foreign words for
centuries, and many are in common use.
   Shirt is ``waishatsu'' _ actually from ``white shirt'' _ and it
will be found on the laundry list next to the ``terebi'' (TV) on
the ``teiburu'' (table) at your ``hoteru'' (hotel).
   Not all borrowed words retain their original shape or meaning.
   ``Handoru'' comes from ``handle'' but means steering wheel.
   ``Rihabiri'' is a shortened ``rehabilitation.''
   Japanese people think of such imports as katakana words because
that is the way they're written, said Tatsuo Miyajima, a department
head at the National Language Research Institute in the Ministry of
Education.
   ``Bureaucrats are fond of katakana words, but not so much as
people in advertising, sports and high-technology areas. When they
speak Japanese, they use English words. They know the Japanese
words, but it's easier to use English words.''
   Miyajima added that many people think foreign words are used too
much, but the proliferation continues, especially from American
English.
   He said his institute refrains from taking a position for or
against borrowed words.
   English is another great borrower of foreign words, he noted,
``and that makes the language more powerful, so why shouldn't we
have foreign words.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Mon PMs Oct. 16</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891009-0150 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-09-89 0710EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a i PM-BowlerHats Adv17   10-09 0634</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bowler Hats, Adv 17,0661</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv17</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Tues PMs Oct. 17 or Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Americans Taking a Fancy to English Bowler Hat</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto Planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By COTTEN TIMBERLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The bowler hat, enduring symbol of the Englishman,
is catching the fancy of Americans.
   Although it has been disappearing from London's financial
district where it once was common, exports of bowlers are growing,
particularly to the United States, experts say.
   ``There's been a marked increase in the number being sold to
Americans,'' said Richard Stephenson, managing director of the
Picadilly hatters James Lock and Co.
   There is also demand from France, where gray bowlers are worn to
the horse races, and from Australia and Africa.
   Overall sales are 25 percent higher than in the mid-1980s, with
most of the growth coming from foreign sales, Stephenson said.
   ``We are selling more,'' said Derek Bedford, managing director
of Christy and Co., Britain's biggest hat maker.
   In Britain today, however, bowler-wearers are viewed by some as
mildly eccentric.
   David Green, an 89-year-old insurance underwriter, explained why
he has worn one for 65 years.
   ``They are smart. It used to be when people dressed smartly the
proper thing to wear was a bowler. I've just kept on with it.''
   Bowlers also are good to grow geraniums in, he said.
   Bedford attributes the recent upturn to increased demand for
bowlers as riding hats and as women's fashion head wear.
   ``We have seen some sort of designer ranges in very strong
colors with holes cut in them and bells sewed on them,'' Bedford
said. ``You do see some very odd derivatives.''
   Bowlers cost $113 to $139 each, and Americans are not buying
them as a gimmick or for souvenirs, Stephenson said.
   ``The vast majority are buying this with every intention of
wearing it.'' But Bedford said, ``We are really finding in the home
market things quieter than we would like.''
   Made of rabbit fur hardened with shellac, bowlers still are
handcrafted through 47 steps over the course of eight weeks,
Bedford said.
   The hats date back to 1850, when William Coke, a Norfolk farmer,
asked James Lock to make a hard hat that would protect his
gamekeepers from overhead branches while they rode their horses.
   Lock designed a close-fitting domed hat and had it made by
London hatters Thomas and William Bowler.
   According to bowler lore, Coke tried out the hat by jumping on
it.
   James Lock has sold the hard hats ever since, calling them Cokes
after the first customer. But the Bowler brothers also branched out
on their own, and their name stuck.
   In the United States, the hat became known as a derby because it
was worn to the Kentucky Derby horse race.
   In 1880s Britain, it became fashionable to wear a bowler in
town, and it was popular among lawyers, brokers, and bankers.
   ``It's particularly associated with London: the pinstriped suit,
the rolled umbrella and the bowler hat,'' Stephenson said.
   But they also were worn by off-duty army officers and by the
foremen of shipyards and mills in northern England.
   They still are part of the uniform worn on parade by the Orange
Order of Northern Ireland Protestants.
   The Duke of Windsor sometimes wore a bowler, as did Charlie
Chaplin. Winston Churchill wore a square-crowned variation.
   During the 1920s and 1930s, up to a million bowlers were
produced annually in factories around Stockport and Manchester, in
northwest England.
   The bowler went into decline after World War II. The spread of
cars meant people didn't need hats as much to keep warm, and dress
became less formal.
   After the war, Christy bought the failing Stockport factories,
which altogether employed 3,500 people. Christy currently has 350
employees making all kinds of hats, including some 50,000 bowlers a
year.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Tues PMs Oct. 17</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891009-0151 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-09-89 0711EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a i PM-Alexander'sLibrary Adv18   10-09 0782</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Alexander's Library, Adv 18,0803</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv18</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Wed PMs Oct. 18 or Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Egyptians Seek New Cultural Leadership for Alexander's Capital</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIMI MANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When Alexander the Great founded his capital
on Egypt's Mediterranean coast, he intended it to dominate the
world. It did, but not through military force as he imagined.
   Alexandria dominated through knowledge and culture, and at the
heart of its glory was the greatest library in the history of the
world.
   The Library of Alexandria lasted for hundreds of years after the
conqueror's death in Babylon at age 33 but it disappeared with few
traces early in the Christian era.
   Now, almost 2,000 years later, Egypt is embarking on a project
to restore Alexandria's cultural prominence by creating a new
library as a symbol of where Egypt's been and where it's going.
   ``We want others to see Egypt from the right point of view, as a
country of civilization,'' said Ahmed Fathy Sorour, Egypt's
minister of education, who is heading the project.
   ``We are much more than keepers of the pyramids. We are reviving
the concept of the Alexandria Library ... in order to prove to the
world that Egypt's civilization didn't go away but is a living
tradition.''
   The site is ready and the design chosen for the projected $180
million-complex that officials say will bring new life to an old
but honored city.
   The site is prime Mediterranean seafront, backed by the bustle
of Alexandria's 4 million people. On the horizon is the
10th-century fortress of Qait Bey, built where one of the Seven
Wonders of the Ancient World, the Pharos Lighthouse, purportedly
stood.
   The design by the Norwegian architectural firm Snoehetta is for
the new Alexandria Library to be a sweeping circle of concrete,
steel, glass and stone _a symbol of the sun.
   If an international fund-raising drive now under way succeeds
and the project meets its schedule, the library complex will be
completed by 1995.
   Recapturing ancient glory won't be easy, for few cities have a
more impressive early history than Alexandria's.
   Founded in 331 B.C., it beckoned the greats of its time, who in
turn gave the world a harvest of their best thoughts and
inventions: the pipe organ, the Archimedes screw, the atlas and
12-month, 365-day year, grammar and geography, geometry and
trigonometry, steam and fire engines, coin-operated machines, city
planning, and cataloging.
   From Alexandria came news that the Earth revolved around the
sun. Alexandrian scholars calculated the circumference of the Earth
to within 50 miles and the length of the solar year to within six
minutes.
   Poetry and prose abounded. They emptied from the
Athens-Alexandria axis into ports around the world, Greek becoming
Roman becoming Western heritage.
   Alexandrian culture revolved around an academic complex called
the Moseion, a think tank for Mediterranean intellectuals with the
freedom and the means to create at will. At the heart of the
Moseion was the library.
   Both were thriving by 285 B.C., a half-century before
establishment of a second, even greater Alexandria Library known to
scholars as the daughter library. It eventually contained an
estimated 500,000 volumes, a trove so vast 120 parchment scrolls
were required to catalog it.
   The collection included the 200,000 volumes of the Pergamum
Library, carted away from what is now Turkey by love-smitten Mark
Antony as a gift for Cleopatra.
   Debate continues over the fate of the ancient Alexandria
libraries. Some historians contend they were destroyed during
Jewish revolts of A.D. 115-117. Others say Christians who rioted
against pagan ways in A.D. 391 destroyed them.
   There appears little evidence the institutions survived long
enough to be destroyed by Arab invaders hundreds of years later, as
many early Western scholars wrote.
   Whatever happened, the libraries and records about them were so
thoroughly demolished that nobody knows for certain what they
looked like or even where they stood.
   The idea to revive the Alexandria Library was born in 1974.
University of Alexandria officials saw it as a way to perpetuate a
literary and cultural heritage long associated with their city,
still an educational headquarters for more than 80,000 students.
   They decided the first step would be a new library, but by the
time Hosni Mubarak, Egypt's president, laid the cornerstone June
26, 1988, the library had become an academic and social center. It
was to include a conference center, a planetarium, a scientists'
Hall of Fame, a calligraphy museum and other facilities.
   ``It's unfair for others to look on Egypt only as a developing
country struggling toward its economic development,'' Education
Minister Sorour said. ``The West owes much to other cultures,
including Egypt and later the Arabs.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Wed PMs Oct. 18</NOTE>
</DOC>
