<FILEID>AP-NR-10-09-89 0712EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a i PM-Brazil-Abortion Adv19   10-09 0695</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Brazil-Abortion, Adv 19,0717</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv19</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Thurs PMs Oct. 19 or Thereafter</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Feminist Groups Launch Brazil's First Pro-Choice Campaign ^By KEN
SILVERSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Feminist groups in traditionally
Roman Catholic Brazil have launched the country's first pro-choice
abortion campaign.
   Though abortion is illegal, except when the mother's life is
endangered due to preganancy or in cases of rape, independent
researchers say 3 million to 5 million clandestine abortions take
place a year.
   That would make Brazil the world's leader, accounting for 4
percent to 7 percent of the World Health Organization's estimate of
roughly 65 million abortions that take place each year.
   Ivany Buzzo, director of the Feminist Health Collective, based
in Sao Paulo, said Brazilian women have been discussing abortion
for more than 10 years but never lobbied for legalization.
   ``Abortion is an extremely delicate issue in Brazil,
particularly with the church's influence,'' said Ms. Buzzo, a
leader of the pro-choice drive.
   About 85 percent of Brazil's 145 million people are listed as
Roman Catholics.
   The pro-choice campaign was officially launched at the 10th
National Feminist Meeting in mid-September.
   The coalition is planning street rallies, a media campaign and
public debates and will lobby Congress in support of a bill
introduced in early September by Rep. Jose Genoino of the
pro-Marxist Workers Party, calling for the legalization of abortion
during the first three months of pregnancy.
   ``Abortion is a human rights and class question,'' Ms. Buzzo
said. ``Everyone knows where the clandestine abortion clinics are,
including the government, so for upper- and middle-class women it's
essentially legal.''
   The average cost of an illegal abortion runs from $200 to $850.
But even $200 is far beyond the means of the majority of women.
   ``It's pure hypocrisy,'' Genoino said. ``Brazil is the world
champion in abortions. But the law forces poor women to risk their
life if they want to terminate their pregnancies.''
   Carmen Barroso, a sociologist with Sao Paulo's Carlos Chagas
Research Foundation, estimated that about 10,000 women die each
year after using crude methods for self-induced abortions, such as
knitting needles.
   His research also indicates that about 200,000 women a year are
admitted to public hospitals due to medical problems stemming from
self-induced abortions.
   Feminist groups also complain that in the case of rape, legal
requirements are so stringent that few Brazilian women are able to
get abortions on those grounds.
   Rape victims need reports from the police and the government's
Legal Medical Institute confirming a rape occurred. A judge then
must authorize the abortion.
   ``By the time all the requirements are met, the child is already
in school,'' Ms. Buzzo said.
   In addition, the Legal Medical Institute won't classify an
attack as rape unless the victim has physical injuries and if sperm
is found in the vagina. If a woman did not ``resist,'' Brazilian
law does not consider rape to have taken place.
   Only 20 percent of the women who go to the institute claiming
they were raped are able to have the crime classified as such, Ms.
Buzzo claimed.
   She said few judges will authorize an abortion even if all
requirements are met because of personal opposition or fear of
negative publicity.
   In 1987, Rio de Janeiro became the first city to pass specific
legislation implementing the legal-abortion law and two public
hospitals were designated to perform abortions on rape victims. The
need for a judge's authorization was dropped.
   But figures from the Rio de Janeiro State Health Department
showed only two women had legal abortions nearly two years after
the law went into effect.
   ``Few women have the courage to admit they were raped,'' said
Dr. Sara Sorreltino, also a member of the Feminist Health
Collective. ``They don't know about the law, or they are unable to
prove the attack took place.''
   Pro-choice supporters don't believe legalization of abortion
will take place any time soon. Genoino estimated that only 50 of
Brazil's 570 congressmen will support his bill.
   But Ms. Buzzo contended, ``A democratic society must grant women
the right to bear a child or not. It's going to be a struggle, but
ultimately we'll win.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Thurs PMs Oct. 19</NOTE>
</DOC>
