<SECOND>BC-History, Adv 15,0491</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv15</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Oct. 15</HEAD>
<HEAD>Today In History</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Today is Sunday, October 15th, the 288th day of 1989. There are
77 days left in the year.
   Today's Highlight in History:
   Twenty-five years ago, on Oct. 15, 1964, it was announced that
Soviet leader Nikita S. Khrushchev had been removed from office. He
was succeeded as premier by Alexei N. Kosygin and as Communist
Party secretary by Leonid I. Brezhnev.
   On this date:
   In 1860, eleven-year-old Grace Bedell of Westfield, N.Y., wrote
a letter to presidential candidate Abraham Lincoln, suggesting he
would look better if he grew a beard.
   In 1914, the Clayton Antitrust Act was passed.
   In 1917, Mata Hari, a Dutch dancer who had spied for the
Germans, was executed by a firing squad outside Paris.
   In 1928, the Graf Zeppelin, a German dirigible, landed in
Lakehurst, N.J., on its first commercial flight across the Atlantic.
   In 1937, the Ernest Hemingway novel, ``To Have and Have Not,''
was published.
   In 1939, New York Municipal Airport, later renamed LaGuardia
Airport, was dedicated.
   In 1945, the former premier of Vichy France, Pierre Laval, was
executed.
   In 1946, Nazi war criminal Hermann Goering poisoned himself one
day before he was to be executed.
   In 1951, the television situation comedy ``I Love Lucy,''
starring Lucille Ball and Desi Arnaz, premiered on CBS.
   In 1966, President Lyndon Johnson signed a bill creating the
Department of Transportation.
   In 1969, peace demonstrators staged activities across the
country, including a candlelight march around the White House, as
part of a campaign against the Vietnam War.
   In 1976, in the first debate of its kind, vice presidential
nominees Walter F. Mondale and Bob Dole faced off in Houston.
   Ten years ago: In El Salvador, the military government of Gen.
Carlos Humberto Romero was overthrown by lower-ranking army
officers, forcing Romero to leave the country with other top
officials.
   Five years ago: Three European researchers _ Niels K. Jerne,
Georges J.F. Koehler and Cesar Milstein _ were awarded the Nobel
Prize in medicine for their contributions to the field of
immunology.
   One year ago: The Los Angeles Dodgers defeated the Oakland A's,
5-4, in the World Series opener that featured a dramatic
game-winning home run by an injured Kirk Gibson.
   Today's Birthdays: Economist John Kenneth Galbraith is 81.
Author-historian Arthur M. Schlesinger Jr. is 72. Author Mario Puzo
is 69. Chrysler chairman Lee Iacocca is 65. Actress Linda Lavin is
52. Actress-director Penny Marshall is 44. Musician Richard
Carpenter is 43. Tennis player Roscoe Tanner is 38. Singer Tito
Jackson is 36. Britain's Duchess of York (formerly Sarah Ferguson)
is 30.
   Thought for Today: ``We used to do things for posterity, now we
do things for ourselves and leave the bill to posterity.''
_Anonymous.
  
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Advance for Sunday, Oct. 15.</NOTE>
</DOC>
