<SECOND>BC-History, Adv21,0471</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv21</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Friday Oct. 21</HEAD>
<HEAD>Today In History</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Today is Saturday, Oct. 21, the 294th day of 1989. There are 71
days left in the year.
   Today's highlight in history:
   On Oct. 21, 1805, the Battle of Trafalgar took place off the
coast of Spain. A British fleet commanded by Adm. Horatio Nelson
defeated a combined French and Spanish fleet, thwarting the plans
of Napoleon I to invade England. Nelson was killed.
   On this date:
   In 1797, the U.S. frigate Constitution, also known as ``Old
Ironsides,'' was launched in Boston Harbor.
   In 1879, Thomas Edison invented a workable electric light at his
laboratory in Menlo Park, N.J.
   In 1917, members of the U.S. Army's 1st Division training in
Luneville, France, became the first Americans to see action on the
front lines of World War I.
   In 1944, during World War II, U.S. troops captured Aachen, the
first large German city to fall to the Allies.
   In 1945, women in France were allowed to vote for the first time.
   In 1959, the Guggenheim Museum, designed by architect Frank
Lloyd Wright, opened in New York.
   In 1960, Democrat John F. Kennedy and Republican Richard M.
Nixon clashed in their fourth and final presidential debate,
televised from New York.
   In 1966, more than 140 people, most of them children, were
killed when a coal waste landslide engulfed a school and several
houses in south Wales.
   In 1967, thousands of demonstrators opposed to the Vietnam War
tried to storm the Pentagon after a peaceful rally in Washington by
some 50,000 protesters.
   In 1971, President Nixon nominated Lewis F. Powell and William
H. Rehnquist to the Supreme Court, following the resignations of
Justices Hugo L. Black and John M. Harlan.
   In 1976, Saul Bellow won the Nobel Prize for literature, the
first American so honored since John Steinbeck in 1962.
   Ten years ago: Israeli Foreign Minister Moshe Dayan resigned in
protest of Prime Minister Menachem Begin's continued hard line on
Palestinian autonomy.
   Five years ago: President Reagan and Democrat Walter F. Mondale
clashed on issues including leadership and defense as they met in
Kansas City, Mo., for their second debate of the 1984 campaign.
   One year ago: A federal grand jury in New York indicted former
Philippine President Ferdinand E. Marcos and his wife, Imelda, on
charges of fraud and racketeering.
   Today's Birthdays: Conductor Sir Georg Solti is 77. Jazz
trumpeter Dizzy Gillespie is 72. Baseball hall-of-famer Whitey Ford
is 61. Rock singer Manfred Mann is 49. Actress Carrie Fisher is 33.
   Thought for Today: ``Youth is a blunder; manhood a struggle; old
age a regret.'' _Benjamin Disraeli, British statesman (1804-1881).
</TEXT>
