<FIRST>s i BC-APN--ItalianBicycling Adv22-2Takes   10-09 0778</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-APN--Italian Bicycling, Adv 22-2 Takes,0792</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv22</HEAD>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Oct. 22</HEAD>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<HEAD>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 2 b&amp;w photos.
ColorFoto subscribers get 1 35mm slide.)    </HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Come along on a ride on a bicycle built for two,
through a scenic area of Italy that has changed little over the
centuries. It's really the best way to see the countryside and meet
the people, but couch potatoes had best spend a while getting in
shape before setting out on a pedal-power tour.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>BY JOE McGOWAN Jr.</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SIRMIONE, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Imagine days of gliding through scenes
from Roman antiquity on a bicycle, with midmorning stops for
cappuccino, streamside lunches of fresh-baked bread, cheese,
prosciutto and wine and evenings in luxurious villas.
   Thousands of people, young and old, athlete and couch potato,
are finding travel by bicycle an exhilarating way of really seeing
the countryside, talking to people and finding historic or cultural
locales rarely available to those speeding through on
air-conditioned tour buses.
   Many adventurous souls are setting off on bicycle trips on their
own, loading their two-wheelers with clothing, bedrolls and
necessities. Others are letting a tour company make lodging
arrangements, plan an itinerary, schedule meals and provide a van
to haul luggage.
   Bicycle tours are available through most European countries,
most areas of the United States, Central and South America and even
the Soviet Union and China.
   I and my wife chose one of the most experienced biking and
walking tour operators, Butterfield and Robinson of Toronto, and
rode from near Milan, Italy, to Venice on a bicycle built for two,
a French-made 10-speed tandem. You can ship your own bike or the
tour operator will provide custom-made bicycles.
   The American Bicycle Federation says the number of bicyclers in
this country increased from 78 million to 88 million since 1985.
   It is expected the bicycle craze will spurt again now that
American Greg LeMond has won the prestigious Tour de France.
   Several states hold popular cross-state bicycle tours. One of
the most grueling is the Ride the Rockies tour that this year
covered 361 miles and went over 11,990-foot Loveland Pass. Tour
director Paul Balaguer said 3,500 people applied for the tour,
which is limited to 2,000.
   Our Northern Italy group included 23 Americans _ people from all
walks of life from all parts of the United States. Ages ranged from
about 30 to the 60s. Tour operators said the eldest to date had
been a 78-year-old man.
   Some had done nothing more to train for the trip than their
usual tennis or golf game. They also were a little stiff and sore
the first day or two, but that quickly went away. My wife and I had
bicycled about 30 miles on Saturdays and Sundays for two months
before the tour and found the tour a breeze.
   Bicycle helmets and biking gloves are strongly recommended and
an athletic shoe with a firm sole is a good idea. Otherwise,
clothing is left up to the individual. On the tour, attire ranged
from skin-tight bicycling outfits to shorts, T-shirts and slacks. A
lightweight rain jacket is recommended, for chilly mornings and
afternoon showers.
   Our group gathered in the lobby of a Milan hotel and then it was
off by bus to Sirmione, on a peninsula on the southern shore of
Lake Garda, Italy's largest. At the tip, a modern hydrofoil
passenger boat cruised past the ruins of a Roman spa.
   Idling past sidewalk cafes, coffee shops and tourists, the bus
squeezed through a narrow passageway at a historic castle, then
deposited our group at the steps of Villa Cortine, the first of
several luxurious villas where our palates would be pampered at
multicourse meals and our bodies rested in regal suites.
   Our two guides _ Jennifer, a Toronto lawyer, and Nick, whose
future plans include screenwriting in New York _ showed us our
bicycles and gave us an orientation on safety, including the
required wearing of helmets and a caution against braking hard with
only the front brake (it can throw you over the handlebars).
   They discussed the daily routine: breakfast together and then to
the bicycles, which would be checked and ready. The cyclists were
encouraged to set their own pace and see the sights. Some raced off
each morning on optional side trips that saw them travel up to 50
miles in a day. Others stopped to take photographs, visit with the
natives, enjoy a cappuccino or espresso and purchase postcards,
still completing the average 30 miles a day in time for a swim at
the villa.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891009-0166 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-09-89 1516EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>s i BC-APN--ItalianBicycling Adv22-1stAdd   10-09 0657</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-APN--Italian Bicycling, Adv 22-1st Add,0670</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv22</HEAD>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Oct. 22</HEAD>
<HEAD>SIRMIONE, Italy: the villa.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Detailed instructions for each day's route were handed out at
breakfast with a caveat that directions are subject to personal
interpretation and ``one person's `bear right at the cross' could
be another's `hard right at the T-intersection.''' And, said the
guides, ``remember _ getting lost is part of the adventure.''
   A sample instruction read ``2 km (kilometers) from the tower,
turn right at intersection following signs for Vaccarolo and San
Pietro, not Solferino. (At this intersection the abandoned Abbey of
San Firgillo can be seen directly in front of you.)''
   Tours are graded by level of difficulty from the Northern Italy
level one (rolling hills and generally level, but with one hill
where we pushed the tandem to the top) to the level four Giro
D'Italia, described as ``a challenging route through the hills of
Tuscany and Umbria ... designed for the enthusiastic and
experienced cyclist.''
   An example of the magnificent villas chosen for touring
bicyclers was the Villa Corner in Cavasagra, built in 1500 and
named for a queen, Caterina Cornaro. The villa was extensively
rebuilt in 1700 by a Palladian architect.
   Today it has manicured grounds, a vineyard, huge pool, spa,
tennis courts and suites the size of some American town houses.
After we finished the tour and went sightseeing in Venice, the room
at our pensione was the size of the walk-in closet in our Villa
Corner suite.
   The tour stayed on side roads with light traffic. Even when the
cyclists pedaled into larger cities such as Verona, they found
Italian motorists to be considerate. Thousands of Italians pedal to
school, to work or to the market, but safety helmets are unknown
and ours brought many curious glances.
   Sights along the way included ancient and modern churches,
centuries-old family estates, more castles than could be counted,
family-operated wineries and a wedding celebration.
   In Verona there was a wine lecture and tasting at the Instituto
Enologico Italiano, a tour of the ancient Roman arena and the opera
house, a visit to the balcony of Romeo and Juliet fame and a walk
through the crowded stalls in the marketplace where we ate
bambolino _ calorie-laden fried dough sprinkled with sugar.
   One day's highlights included a tour of Lugano, one of the
countless small wineries. This one, operated by Luigi Fraccaroli,
produced a delicate white wine, samples of which were offered to
the American cyclists. A tractor arrived, pulling a trailer with
the first day's pickings of the new grape harvest. The tourists
watched as the grapes were crushed.
   On day five, Jennifer and Nick surprised the group with a picnic
feast in the courtyard of an ancient castle on a hilltop outside
the walled city of Soave. They loaded a table with fruits, cheeses,
meats, breads and wines, highlighted by bunches of fresh-picked
wildflowers. A group photograph was taken for posterity.
   After a day's ride, there was a cocktail party where the day's
events were discussed. Then, a sumptuous dinner.
   One evening menu read: crepes, pasta and smoked ham, pasta e
fagioli alla veneta (traditional pasta and beans in a cream soup),
roast beef al Pepe or sole a la Venetian, then choices from a
breathtaking dessert tray, followed by hearty Italian coffee, all
accompanied by fine Italian wines.
   Since it was harvest time, bowls of incredibly sweet grapes were
placed in reception areas and guest rooms.
   All too soon, the bicyclists reached Villa Corner at Cavasagra,
outside Venice, the final destination.
   ``This was my first tour, but I expect we'll do it again,'' said
Jack Blakemore of Greenbrae, Calif.
   Kathy Hillis of Nevada City, Calif., said: ``I loved talking to
all the people. It was really neat to ride down the road and say
`buon giorno' to the villagers.''
   ``It was one unforgettable incident after another,'' said Angelo
Capozzi of Tiburon, Calif.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>END ADV</NOTE>
</DOC>
