<HEAD>For Release Anytime</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Video View: Home Video News and Reviews</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Checking Out'' (Virgin Vision. VHS-Beta, $89.95. Rated R)
   
   Ray Macklin is perfectly healthy but obsessed with the certainty
he's about to die. His pursuit of an illness to cure makes
``Checking Out'' very funny and very strange, just right for a
night at home.
   Jeff Daniels, with his classic good looks, is wonderful as
Macklin, whose life is thrown off kilter when his jokester pal
drops dead at a barbecue just before telling the punchline.
   Macklin's maudlin attitude hits his wife, Jenny (Melanie
Mayron), whom he virtually ignores except to tell her not to use
salt, and his boss (Michael Tucker), who suddenly is faced with a
crazed employee.
   The boss tries to calm Macklin with such words of wisdom about
his friend's death as: ``It's the hotel of life. You check out and
they come and make up the room.''
   When Macklin actually faces death, he imagines a heaven that
looks like a tacky beach resort and offers all the freedom of a
strict grammar school.
   Jokes about death pervade the movie, and if they are a bit
off-putting at the start, they become endearing and actually in the
end serve to celebrate the joy of life.
   The acting is fine, with everyone treating the bizarre material
as if it was most ordinary. Careful viewers can catch David Byrne
of the Talking Heads in a small role as a bartender.
   ``Checking Out'' was written by Joe Eszterhas (``Flashdance''
and ``Jagged Edge'') and directed by David Leland (``Wish You Were
Here'').
   _ By Mary MacVean, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Say Anything'' (CBS-Fox Video. VHS-Beta, $89.98. Rated PG-13)
   
   In ``Say Anything,'' a pair of blushing teen-agers fall ... oh,
don't say it, ummm, well ... really? No? Really? Oh, I'm so happy!
I love you, too!
   It's that kind of movie. It's predictable. But it's tender. And
it accurately captures those awkward, lovely, painful moments of
being both in love and a teen-ager.
   The story centers on Lloyd (John Cusack), a likeable guy who is
a little low on ambition, and Diane Court (Ione Skye), school
valedictorian, hyper-achiever and a striking beauty. Lloyd's pals
call her ``a brain, a brain trapped in the body of a game show
hostess.''
   The romance would flourish if weren't for Diane's
over-protective father. When dad asks about Lloyd's goal in life,
Lloyd says point-blank that it's to spend as much time possible
with his daughter.
   Cameron Crowe, who wrote ``Fast Times at Ridgemont High,'' makes
his directing debut with ``Say Anything'' and wonderfully captures
off-beat and witty nuances of teen tribulations.
   There is, for instance, Lloyd's friend who wrote 65 songs about
her boyfiend Joe _ who dumped her. In another scene, Lloyd gets an
earful of advice from the boys hanging out a convenience store
parking lot. That leads Lloyd to ask them why, if they know so much
about women, are they at a Gas-n-Sip on a Saturday night.
   The big flaw is an annoying competitive sub-plot concerning
Diane's father, who is in trouble with the Internal Revenue
Service. It nags on the main plot of the struggling romance like a
bad habit.
   But love endures and this charming film overcomes its plot
problems to leave viewers feeling warm and fuzzy, but hardly
surprised.
   __ By Patricia Bibby, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Motion Picture Association of America rating definitions:
   G _ General audiences. All ages admitted.
