<HEAD>For Release Anytime</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>On Show: Museum and Gallery Exhibits and Shows</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOLORES BARCLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Arts Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The San Diego Museum of Art will have the
largest collection of Imperial eggs on exhibit since the Russian
Revolution of 1917 as part of the Soviet Arts Festival.
   The ornate, jewel-encrusted eggs, crafted by Peter Carl Faberge,
are coming to San Diego from all over the world: the Forbes
magazine collection, Queen Elizabeth II, the New Orleans Museum of
Art, the Cleveland Museum of Art. Eight eggs from the Kremlin's
Armory Museum have never before been exhibited in the United States.
   The only egg based in San Diego is the diamond-studded Pine Cone
Egg, on loan from John Kroc, owner of the San Diego Padres and
widow of the founder of the McDonald's hamburger chain.
   The Faberge eggs mirrored the excess of the Russian Imperial
Court. The first egg was commissioned by Czar Alexander III who
gave it to his wife, Marie Feodorovna on Easter morning in 1885.
The white egg opened to reveal a golden yolk, a gold chicken and a
ruby egg.
   About 55 Imperial eggs were made until 1916, but only 43 are
known to still exist.
   Quilts, scrimshaw and decoys were once considered homey
additions to everyday life. Now they're known as folk art.
   Decorative figures, weathervanes, whirligigs, farm tools,
architecture, toys, household goods and trade signs help make the
folk art exhibit at the New York Historical Society a treat and
celebrates the craftsmanship and genius of our ancestors.
   The show, ``An American Sampler: Folk Art From the Shelburne
Museum,'' features more than 120 works from the Vermont museum's
Americana collection, and runs through Jan. 7.
   Oct. 15 marks the official opening of Meseo Chicano, billed as
Arizona's first Hispanic museum. Founded by Chicanos Por La Causa,
a community development corporation, the new museum opens with
``Arte, Sweat and Tears.'' The show features work of Arizona
Hispanic artists and of Mexican painter Jose Luis Cuevas and runs
through Jan. 15.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Here is a list of other current shows this season at some
museums and galleries around the country:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Genest Gallery and Sculpture Garden, Lambertville, N.J.:
   Recent works by Elisabetta Marcucci, an Italian painter whose
impressionistic technique focuses on the female form and nature.
Through Nov. 26.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Los Angeles County Museum of Art:
   Works by Robert Longo, who combines sculpture, video and
drawing. Through Dec. 31.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Greg Kucera Gallery, Seattle:
   ``Taboo,'' an exhibit of controversial art by 20 artists,
including Anores Serrano, Gale McCall and Joel-Peter Witkin.
Through Oct. 29.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   The Heard Museum, Phoenix:
   ``Fourth Biennial Native American Fine Arts Invitational,''
showcasing eight Indian artists from the United States and Canada.
Oct. 21-Spring 1990.
   ``Exotic Illusions: Art, Romance and the Marketplace.''
Selections from the Heard's permanent collection demonstrate how
artists from Africa, Oceania and the Americas have produced exotic
materials for external consumption: pottery, carvings, paintings,
jewelry. Through Dec. 31.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Phoenix Art Museum:
   Cowboy Artists of America annual exhibition. Oct. 20-Nov. 19.
   ``Rodin: Sculpture from the B. Gerald Cantor Collections.''
Through Dec. 3.
   Sino-Tibetan bronzes. Through Dec. 31.
   ``Word and Image.'' Works by Chinese painters and calligraphers.
Through Oct. 29.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   The Dallas Museum of Art:
   ``Impressionists and Modern Masters in Dallas: Monet to
Mondrian.'' Through Oct. 22.
   ``Patrick Faigenbaum: Roman Portraits.'' Through Nov. 12.
   ``Artful Deception: The Craft of the Forger.'' Oct. 15 to Dec.
17.
   ``American Art, 1700 to 1950.'' Through April 8.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Amon Center, Fort Worth, Texas:
   ``Bourke-White: A Retrospective.'' Through Nov. 12.
   ``Hand, Eye and Stone: The Lithographs of Thomas Hart Benton.''
Through Nov. 19.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   The Museum of Fine Arts, Boston:
   ``Mary Cassatt: The Color Prints.'' Through Nov. 5.
   ``Objects and Subjects, 1969-1986.'' Works by Lucas Samaras.
Through Nov. 12.
   ``Textile Masterpieces.'' Through Dec. 31.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   J. Paul Getty Museum, Malibu, Calif.:
   ``15th and 16th century Italian Drawings.'' The Renaissance and
Mannerist periods. Through Oct. 22.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   GWS Galleries, Southport, Conn.:
   ``Art From People's Republic of China.'' Second major exhibit in
United States of 30 artists who live throughout China. Oct. 15-Nov.
12.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   M.H. de Young Memorial Museum, San Francisco:
   ``California Colorists: Society of Six.'' Through December.
   ``American Paintings from the Manoogian Collection,'' 19th
century American paintings. Through Nov. 26.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   The Museum of Contemporary Art, Chicago:
   Arnulf Rainer restrospective. Through Oct. 15.
   ``MCA Presents: Video Art From Our First Two Decades.'' Through
mid-November.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Solomon R. Guggenhein Museum, New York:
   First major American exhibition of works by Italian artist Mario
Merz, who integrates natural materials into his work. Through Nov.
26.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   The Museum of Fine Arts, Houston:
   ``The Grand Elegance Venice: Costumes of Mariano Fortuny.'' Over
50 gowns, costumes and accessories created by the Venetian painter,
engraver, theater designer and photographer Fortuny (1871-1949).
Oct. 15-Dec. 31.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   The Seattle Art Museum, Seattle:
   ``Shadowy Evidence: The Photography of Edward S. Curtis and His
Contemporaries.'' Curtis was one of photography's masters of
pictorialism, an early 20th century practice characterized by soft
focus and eccentric composition. Through Nov. 19.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Portland Art Museum, Oregon:
   Minor White, a photography retrospective. Through Nov. 12.
   ``Grafica Popular,'' 20th century Mexican prints. Through Nov.
19.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Washburn Gallery, New York:
   ``Anne Ryan: A Centennial.'' Paintings, collages of artist-poet
Anne Ryan (1889-1954). Through Nov. 4.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Nerlino Gallery, New York:
   Mantle sculptures, lithographs and multiple exposure sepia
photos by Mary Clare Galvin. Through Nov. 1.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   International Center of Photography, New York:
   ``I Dream a World: Portraits of Black Women Who Changed
America.'' Through Oct. 29.
   ``The Naked Nude.'' A theatrical installation of light, sound,
holograms, photographs and music. Through Oct. 29.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Metropolitan Museum of Art, New York:
   38 compositions by Diego Rodriquez de Silva y Velazquez,
including his ``An Old Woman Cooking Eggs'' (1618) with its
haunting reality, and ``The Forge of Vulcan'' and ``Joseph's
Coat,'' two large works painted during a trip to Italy in 1629-31.
Through Jan. 7.
   ``Masterworks of Ming and Qing Painting From the Forbidden
City.'' Paintings dating from the Ming (1368-1644) and Qing
(1644-1911) dynasties. Through Oct. 29.
   Flemish drawings and prints from 16th and 17th centuries.
Through Nov. 12.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Museum of Modern Art, New York:
   ``Picasso and Braque: Pioneering Cubism.'' Through Jan. 16.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Whitney Museum of American Art, Fairfield County, Stamford,
Conn.:
   ``Realism and Romanticism in 19th Century New England
Seascapes.'' Works of 30 artists ranging from ship portraits and
seascapes to pirate scenes and sunsets. Through Nov. 29.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Phillippe Staib Gallery, New York:
   Bronze sculpture by Louis Derbre. Through Nov. 18.
</TEXT>
