<FIRST>a e BC-WKD--SilentBrotherhood Adv20-22   10-09 0987</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--Silent Brotherhood, Adv 20-22,1012</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv20</HEAD>
<HEAD>$adv21</HEAD>
<HEAD>$adv22</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions, Oct. 20-22, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Books and Authors: Inside America's Racist Underground</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN K. PAULSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Who was Robert Jay Mathews, the white supremacist
who declared war on the United States and led a major terrorist
campaign throughout the American West?
   Kevin Flynn and Gary Gerhardt spent four years tracking his
movements and those of his four dozen followers, and pieced
together a written patchwork quilt that provides some insight into
this group and its activities.
   Their book, ``The Silent Brotherhood,'' published by MacMillan
Inc., is more than a chronology of events that includes the slaying
of Denver radio talk show host Alan Berg in a burst of machine-gun
fire in 1984.
   It explores the underground group's thinking, way of life and
the passions that drove followers to rob armored cars, blow up
churches and take on the U.S. government, which they branded the
``Zionist Occupation Government,'' or ZOG for short.
   It's a tale of bravado and intrigue, murder and passion.
   It also details one of the widest, most expensive criminal
investigations since the Patty Hearst case. By the time it ended,
there were 75 arrests in related cases and five deaths.
   Flynn and Gerhardt, reporters for the Rocky Mountain News, said
the Silent Brotherhood took its name from a poem in a history of
Adolf Hitler's dreaded Wafen SS. The Silent Brotherhood laid
elaborate plans to sabotage dams, water supplies, utilities and
communications lines. Its goal was to transform five Western states
into an Aryan Nation, free of black and Jewish influence.
   To finance their plan, members robbed two banks in Washington
and launched a career of armored car heists that spread to
California.
   They set up a ``doomsday'' assassination squad. If the group was
attacked by authorities, it planned to track and kill statesman
Henry Kissinger, banker David Rockefeller and the heads of the
three television networks, all of whom were perceived as enemies
because they were either Jewish or worked for Jews.
   To prove their resolve, they decided to send a message. On June
18, 1984, they stalked and killed Berg outside his Denver home.
Berg was killed because he was Jewish and because he frequently
attacked group members on his radio program with his acid-tongued
wit.
   The funds from their robberies grew, and included $3.8 million
netted in a bold daylight highway robbery near Ukiah, Calif. This
money was to be shared with other right-wing groups in the United
States, including the Carolina Knights of the KKK in North
Carolina, the Texas Klan, the White Aryan Resistance in California,
and the white supremacist group Aryan Nations.
   The group made a major mistake by leaving behind a gun during a
California heist, and FBI agents tracked Mathews to a home near
Seattle, where he died in a hail of gunfire and flames during a
36-hour standoff.
   The story doesn't end there. In July 1986 at the Aryan World
Congress, Mathews and his followers were honored with medals that
read, ``Should you fall, my friend, another friend will emerge from
the shadows to take your place.''
   In September 1986, a string of bombings took place in Coeur
d'Alene, Idaho, by a group calling itself the Silent Brotherhood
Strike Force II.
   Among those who provided information to the authors were Bruce
Pierce, now serving time in an Illinois prison, who was convicted
in November 1987 of violating Alan Berg's civil rights by killing
him, and Zillah Craig, Mathew's lover who is now raising his
daughter.
   The book is remarkable for its details on groups that pride
themselves on secrecy. However, it still fails to resolve the one
central question, ``Why did they do it?''
   The authors attempt to explain it as part of the ``mountain
man'' mystique and frontier spirit of the Old West, but that fails
to explain the vast allure of groups such as these in the South,
with deep roots in the Civil War.
   Flynn and Gerhardt acknowledge they are not psychologists, but
say they wanted to provide some insight into why racists belong to
such groups.
   ``It's simplistic and easy to put these guys in a jar on a shelf
called nuts and not worry about it,'' Gerhardt said. ``These were
real people not a whole lot different than we are. The difference
is how they carried it out.''
   Flynn said all supremacist groups have several things in common,
such as a charismatic leader, what they view as a superpatriotic
attitude and a shared goal of restoring the United States, not
destroying it.
   In the end, the best clue to the thinking of such groups comes
from Mathews himself, who cheated the FBI out of a chance for
interrogation by choosing death.
   Shortly before he died, Mathews gathered the group together and
asked them to sign a declaration of war against society:
   ``We, the following, being of sound mind and under no duress, do
hereby sign this document of our own free will, stating
forthrightly and without fear that we declare ourselves to be in
full and unrelenting state of war with those forces seeking and
consciously promoting the destruction of our faith and our race.''
   While facing dozens of heavily armed agents, holed up in a house
with a small armory, Mathews was asked what it would take for him
to surrender.
   ``I want parts of eastern Washington, Idaho and Montana set
aside as an Aryan homeland,'' he said.
   In his suicide note, Mathews could only muse as to why the white
FBI agents could turn against one of their own race. It serves as
an epitaph for his paramilitary organization, betrayed in the end
to federal agents by two of his own men.
   ``White men killing white men, Saxon killing Dane;
   ``When will it end? The Aryan's bane?''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, Oct. 20-22</NOTE>
