<FIRST>u f PM-Dollar-Gold     10-09 0273</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0286</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Mostly Lower, Pound Drops, Gold Little Changed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar was mostly lower in early European
trading today, but gained more than 2 cents against the British
pound.
   Gold prices were little changed.
   Currency dealers said trading was quiet because of the Columbus
Day holiday in the United States, and because Canadian financial
institutions were closed for that country's Thanksgiving holiday.
   Dealers said the market is trying to find new direction after
European interest rate hikes, central bank interventions and
weaker-than-expected September U.S. job figures all failed to take
the dollar much lower.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar fell 0.22 yen to a closing 142.23 yen. Later, in
London, it was quoted at 142.65 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning compared with late Friday's
rates, included: 1.8862 West German marks, down from 1.8880; 1.6450
Swiss francs, up from 1.6435; 6.3955 French francs, down from
6.4035; 2.1333 Dutch guilders, down from 2.1350; 1,378.38 Italian
lire, down from 1,380.25; 1.1750 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1760.
   In London, the pound fell. It cost $1.5815 to buy one pound,
compared with $1.6030 late Friday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $363.50 a troy ounce,
compared with late Friday's $363.25. At midmorning, the city's five
major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $362.95.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $363.00, up from $362.80 late
Friday.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $5.13 a troy
ounce, down from Friday's $5.14.
   Financial institutions in Hong Kong were closed today because of
the Chinese Chung Yeung or Grave Sweeping Festival.
</TEXT>
