<FIRST>r f PM-Where'stheGrowth     10-09 0764</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Where's the Growth,0786</SECOND>
<HEAD>Layoffs Abound, But Some Sectors Still Adding Employees</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARIANN CAPRINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   IBM is offering early retirement to 1,000 of its
employees; Borden's plan to reorganize its dairy operations will
cost 7,000 jobs, and the megabuyout of RJR Nabisco will result in
more than 1,600 layoffs.
   Business optimism appears to be dimming, and manufacturers are
becoming more aggressive in cutting costs and people. But a
relatively steady unemployment rate _ which has fluctuated between
5.1 percent and 5.3 percent since April _ means somebody is hiring.
   The question is, who?
   Steven Haugen, an economist with the Bureau of Labor Statistics,
says job growth is concentrated in the service sector, that broad,
amorphous category covering everything from data processing to
theme parks to the neighborhood beauty parlor. Experts say this
sector is creating upwards of 1.5 million jobs a year.
   ``Services is very labor intensive, so it's sucking up all the
workers,'' said John Hekman, a senior economist at the Claremont
Economics Institute in Claremont, Calif.
   In September alone, when the loss of 103,000 manufacturing jobs
inched the unemployment rate up 0.1 percent to 5.3 percent, service
industries added 317,000 jobs. A closer look, however, shows
teachers returning to their classrooms and the ending of a
telephone workers strike were responsible for much of the job
increase.
   But economists point to health care providers, temporary help
agencies, hotels and the entertainment industry as being among the
most consistent ``net adders'' of employees.
   The health care industry is growing at just under 10 percent a
year, said Geoffrey Fenton, a spokesman for Baxter International, a
major medical supplies manufacturer in Deerfield, Ill.
   Baxter added 2,400 jobs in 1988, and Fenton said the payroll
continues to grow this year. Revenue grew 10 percent last year, and
sales were up significantly so far this year, he said.
   Orders to the 6,000 to 7,000 hospitals Baxter supplies are
increasing as an aging population requires more medical care. But
the fastest growing area of new business for Baxter lies in the
sale of ``alternate-site'' products, like intravenous solutions and
dialysis items used at home and in nursing homes. Overall
outpatient care is growing at the rate of about 20 percent
annually, said Hekman.
   On the temporary help scene, Manpower Inc. Chief Executive
Mitchell Fromstein characterized growth as ``meteoric'' over the
last five years. Since the beginning of this year, Fromstein said
Manpower's permanent staff has increased by 1,000 employees.
   ``We're increasing the number of offices we operate by 10
percent a year, and we will do at least that going forward,'' he
said from the company's headquarters in Milwaukee.
   ``We're adding more offices because we can do more business,''
said Fromstein, who noted that the number of people employed
temporarily has tripled since 1982.
   On the entertainment and recreation front, the theme park
business is hot. Walt Disney Co. has added about 4,000 people to
its payroll with the opening of three new attractions at Disney
World in Orlando, Fla. _ Disney-MGM Studios, Typhoon Lagoon water
park and a nighttime entertainment section, said spokesman Erwin
Okun.
   In addition to hiring people to staff the new attractions, Okun
said, increased attendance _ bolstered by an influx of foreign
tourists flush with cash thanks to favorable exchange rates _ has
spurred Disney to create new jobs.
   MCA Inc. is investing $600 million in a Universal Studios movie
park that will compete directly with Disney when it opens in the
spring.
   On the West Coast, MGM Grand Inc. announced plans this month to
build a $700 million movie theme park in Las Vegas that will employ
7,000 people when it opens, tentatively in late 1992.
   The lodging industry is also expanding nationwide. In the 12
months ended in June, 60,000 new hotel jobs had been created,
Hekman said.
   Hyatt Corp., the Chicago-based hotel chain, is adding 3,000
positions this year because of expansion and acquisitions, said
spokeswoman Carrie Reckert.
   Although the loss of manufacturing jobs concerns many
economists, in part because service sector jobs tend to pay less
than industrial work, others don't see this as a severe problem.
They say the manufacturing process has become more efficient and
fewer workers are required.
   ``We shouldn't be concerned if manufacturing is not growing
because we're having a 5 percent (annual) increase in output per
worker,'' Hekman said.
   But the service sector has shown very little productivity gains,
``so as the economy grows, we're moving people out of
high-productivity areas and moving them into the services,'' he
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891009-0187 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-09-89 0804EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights     10-09 0829</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0872</SECOND>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The largest decline in payrolls at auto plants
and other factories in nearly seven years helped push the nation's
jobless rate to 5.3 percent in September, the government said in a
report showing unexpected softness in the economy.
   The civilian unemployment rate was up from 5.2 percent in both
July and August, the Labor Department said Friday.
   Non-farm employers told the government they added a seasonally
adjusted 209,000 jobs in September, more than double a revised
88,000 in August. But nearly all of the growth can be attributed to
special factors.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Americans took out $3.48 billion more in
consumer debt than they paid off in August, the government
reported, resuming their borrowing practices after reducing their
debt in July for the first time in 2{ years.
   Analysts had said the July debt liquidation was a one-time
thing, and forecast continued borrowing in the foreseeable future.
   ``We really haven't become a nation of big savers,'' economist
Sandra Shaber of the Futures Group, a Washington forecasting firm,
said Friday. ``People aren't tearing up their credit cards.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of American Airlines'
second-largest union met with advisers to discuss possible ways to
help management fend off developer Donald Trump's $7 billion buyout
proposal.
   Michael Kelleher, president of the 16,000-member Association of
Professional Flight Attendants, traveled to New York Friday to meet
with ``legal and labor advisers to prepare contingency plans in
light of any events that may transpire,'' said a spokesman for the
independent union.
   Also Friday, Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, D-Texas, exchanged letters with
Trump, expressing concern over the wave of airline takeovers.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Production continued slowly at Boeing Co. plants
as a strike by 57,800 Machinists stretched into its third day
without the company or union scheduling new talks to end the
walkout.
   Also on Friday, Boeing announced it had gained another
multibillion-dollar aircraft order, from Evergreen Airways Corp. of
Taiwan, further adding to the company's huge backlog of airliner
orders.
   Federal mediator Douglas Hammond said no new talks had been
scheduled.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Policy-makers at the Federal Reserve decided
to keep interest rates unchanged in late August, following a period
earlier in the summer when they were nudging rates lower, according
to minutes of the Fed meeting.
   The Federal Open Market Committee voted 10-1 at its Aug. 22
meeting to make no changes in interest rates although it issued a
directive that leaned toward credit-easing if the economy weakened,
according to the minutes released Friday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Deregulation of the airline industry has led
to domination of domestic air travel by a few companies, two
Republican senators said Friday in introducing legislation they say
would increase competition.
   Sens. John C. Danforth, R-Mo., and John McCain, R-Ariz., said
that deregulation has failed to benefit the traveling public,
despite an early flurry of competition, but that their bill is not
a return to regulation.
   Among the bill's provisions is a prohibition against airlines
owning computerized reservation services.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ford Motor Co. has received U.S. regulatory
clearance to buy up to 15 percent of Jaguar PLC.
   Ford received early clearance from the Federal Trade Commission,
which must approve major share acquisitions under the
Hart-Scott-Rodino Act, a Ford U.K. spokesman said Friday.
   Ford announced Sept. 19 that it wanted to buy up to 15 percent
of Jaguar, and left open the option of making a full bid for the
British luxury automaker.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush has rejected a Democratic offer
to pare down a deficit-reduction bill the Senate is about to
consider, removing his capital gains tax cut along with provisions
close to the Democrats' hearts.
   Bush and his Republican Senate allies on Friday branded the
Democratic proposal as inadequate, although negotiations aimed at
finding middle ground seemed possible.
   ``Capital gains is vital,'' Bush said before discussing the
situation with Senate Republicans in the Capitol. ``It's not an
extraneous matter with me.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A small Swedish company has signed a
jackpot deal to sell 25,000 one-armed bandits to the Soviet Union,
the Swedish national news agency TT reported.
   TT said Friday that the company, Bonik AB, was buying existing
machines from all over Sweden and adapting the coin slots for
rubles before transporting them by truck to various towns in the
Soviet Union.
   Bonik almost went bankrupt after Swedish authorities banned the
gambling slot machine 10 years ago.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market gained more ground Friday, in buying attributed
to hopes for an easier Federal Reserve credit policy. The Dow Jones
average of 30 industrials rose 11.96 points to 2,785.52, a new high.
   The dollar finished mixed. Gold prices ended higher.
   Bond prices soared on expectations the Federal Reserve might
soon lower interest rates.
   Coffee futures prices sank for the fourth straight day; corn and
soybeans slumped while livestock, precious metals and oil futures
were mixed.
</TEXT>
