<HEAD>London Shares Lower at Midday on Worries About the Pound</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices were lower at midday Monday, as
investors were unnerved by weakness in the pound just days after
British interest rates were raised.
   Dealers said London's financial community was beginning to
consider that another rise in rates, now at 15 percent, might be a
possibility.
   Some commentators said the pound was put under renewed pressure
by weekend press speculation that a rift had emerged over
management of the economy between Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher
and Chancellor of the Exchequer Nigel Lawson.
   At about 12:15 p.m., the Financial Times-Stock Exchange
100-share index was down 23.4 points, or 1 percent, at 2,254.1,
above its morning minimum of 2,247.9 but lower than its peak of
2,265.2.
   Volume amounted to a modest 252.3 million shares by midday,
compared with 296 million shares at the same time Friday.
