<FILEID>AP-NR-10-09-89 0835EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Britain-ChannelTunnel     10-09 0344</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Britain-Channel Tunnel,0355</SECOND>
<HEAD>Consortium Raises Revenue Forecasts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Anglo-French consortium which is building the
31-mile rail tunnel under the English Channel said Monday it will
cost substantially more to build the link between England and
France.
   The consortium Eurotunnel said the tunnel would cost 7 billion
pounds, (about $11 billion), or 44 percent more than predicted two
years ago, largely because of higher than anticipated costs for
rail cars.
   Eurotunnel Co-chairman Alastair Morton said last week that the
group would have to raise more funds to meet the higher costs, and
that it was embroiled in a cost dispute with its major contractor
Transmanche-Link, which was pegging costs between 5 percent and 10
percent higher.
   Morton said Monday he was sure those difficulties would be
sorted out and that talks with TML were polite and constructive,
contrary to weekend reports that suggested otherwise.
   ``There is no longer a question of should the project be built.
It's going ahead,'' the co-chairman said. ``We would never request
government assistance and their answer would be `no' anyway.''
   Eurotunnel said it raised its revenue projections by 7 percent
for the year 2003 to 819.5 million pounds, or $1.29 billion, from
768.4 million pounds and by 8 percent for the year 2013 to 997.4
million pounds from 923.1 million pounds.
   Eurotunnel shares, which have fallen sharply since the higher
costs were announced, were off 33 pence, or 52 cents, at 535 pence
on London's Stock Exchange Monday morning.
   Morton said the proposed British Rail high-speed rail link
joining London with the tunnel needed to be completed ``as quickly
as possible'' to avoid serious congestion on existing networks.
   On the tunnel work itself, Eurotunnel reported that the boring
machines had ``not yet reached satisfactory production rate,'' but
that modifications were being made.
   Working from both sides of the channel, workers have dug about
half of a service tunnel, but construction of two other tunnels,
which will carry trains in opposite directions, has a long way to
go. Eurotunnel says it will complete the project by mid-1993.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
