<FIRST>u f BC-Britain-Stocks 1stLd-Writethru f0014 10-09 0197</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Britain-Stocks, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0014,0203</SECOND>
<HEAD>London Shares Close Sharply Lower</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout with closing prices.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices fell sharply Monday on London's Stock
Exchange in reaction to the pound's weakness and fears that the
recent hike in British interest rates could lead to a recession.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index fell 30.5
points, or 1.3 percent, to close at 2,247.0, its lowest close since
July 10.
   The index declined throughout the day after opening at its
session high of 2,262.8. The index closed only marginally above the
day's low of 2,242.6.
   The Financial Times 30-share index ended 34.9 points lower at
1,822.9. The Financial Times 500-share index fell 18.94 points to
close at 1,250.43.
   Volume came to 424 million shares, down from Friday's 505.5
million shares.
   Dealers pointed to sterling's drop below 3.0 West German marks
early in the day as the key factor in the market's decline. The
weakness in sterling exacerbated the market's concerns over rising
British interest rates, which now stand at 15 percent, and chances
for recession.
   But dealers attributed part of the price declines to
profit-taking, and said institutions were actively buying the more
recession-proof stocks.
</TEXT>
