<FIRST>d f AM-CentelAcquisition     10-09 0270</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Centel Acquisition,0278</SECOND>
<HEAD>Centel Announces Agreement to Acquire New Cellular Phone Franchise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Centel Corp. announced Monday it has reached an
agreement to purchase the cellular telephone franchise serving the
Aiken, S.C., and Augusta, Ga., area from Pond Branch Telephone Co.
   Terms of the agreement with Pond Branch, based near Aiken, were
not disclosed. The transaction is subject to the minority
shareholder's right of refusal, which may be exercised within 30
days. Completion of the deal is subject to approval by state and
federal regulators.
   Aiken-Augusta, on the South Carolina-Georgia border, has a
population of 406,000 and is located between two other Centel
cellular markets, in Greenville-Spartansburg-Anderson and
Charleston.
   Centel provides cellular service to 41 markets nationwide,
second only to McCaw Communications of Kirkland, Wash.
Chicago-based Centel is the 10th-largest cellular phone company in
terms of customers served, said spokesman William K. White.
   The company said it will have operating control of 46 markets
and interests in 14 others after acquisitions are completed in
Aiken-Augusta; Dothan, Ala.; Laredo, Texas; Petersburg-Colonial
Heights, Va.; and Sioux City, Iowa.
   In addition to its cellular operations, Centel _ which had 1988
revenues of $1.09 billion _ provides local exchange telephone
service through more than 1.5 million access lines in nine states
and supplies electrical service to nearly 136,000 customers in two
states.
   The company recently announced the sale of four of its cable
television operations and has reached definitive agreements to sell
its remaining properties. Centel also is seeking bids for its
business systems operation, which markets, designs and installs
advanced telecommunications and data systems and has more than
18,000 customers.
</TEXT>
