<FILEID>AP-NR-10-09-89 1506EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   10-09 0260</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0271</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soybeans Down Sharply on Word of Good Harvest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices closed lower
Monday on the Chicago Board of Trade as traders reacted to word the
weekend saw the biggest harvest of the season.
   November and January soybeans drifted to contract lows in light
trading, reflecting the harvest news.
   Adding pressure to prices was speculation by traders that the
U.S. Department of Agriculture's crop report due out Thursday will
contain an upward revision of the crop production estimate, said
William Biedermann, an analyst with Allendale Inc. in Chicago.
   Corn prices were pressured by the belief there will be little
additional business from the Soviet Union. The USDA announced late
Friday that the Soviets have purchased 1.1 million metric tons of
corn.
   There is little prospect of more business from the Soviet Union,
Biedermann said.
   Wheat prices were undermined by the dashing of rumors that the
Soviets would buy U.S. wheat. It appears the Soviets would instead
try to rely on domestic production, analysts said.
   The absence of many traders because of the Yom Kippur and
Columbus Day holidays tended to depress prices, according to
analysts.
   At the close, wheat was 3{ cents to 5\ cents lower with the
contract for delivery in December at $4.06\ a bushel; corn was 3
cents to 4\ cents lower with December at $2.35 a bushel; oats were
2} cents to 3{ cents lower with December at $1.40{ a bushel;
soybeans were 5 cents to 11\ cents lower with November at $5.56{ a
bushel.
</TEXT>
