<FIRST>d f AM-ManvilleExpansion     10-09 0179</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Manville Expansion,0185</SECOND>
<HEAD>Manville Board OKs $65 Million Expansion</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Manville Corp. board on Monday approved a $65
million expansion of its fiber glass facility in Waterville, Ohio,
which emphasizes its commitment to the reinforcements market, a
company spokesman said.
   The project will include the expansion of the fiber glass
rovings and chopped strands production, using state-of-the-art
technology, including some recently licensed technology from Nippon
Electric Glass of Otsu, Japan, Manville said in a news release.
   In February, Manville acquired the exclusive North American
rights to manufacture chopped strand products using NEG's
technology. NEG is a leading manufacturer of technical glass
products for a wide range of industries.
   ``We have the technology, the financial resources and the
dedication of our employees to provide our customers with the
highest quality reinforcement products in the world,'' said Richard
A. Kashnow, vice president and general manager of the Denver-based
company's mats, fiber and reinforcements division.
   Manville is the world's largest producer of fiber glass mats and
a leading producer of fiber glass insulation and continuous
filament glass fibers.
</TEXT>
