<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     10-09 0216</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0227</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Futures Prices Rise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil futures prices finished higher in light
holiday trading Monday, led by a seasonal push in heating oil.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the November contract for
domestic heating oil rose 0.59 cent to close at 58.77 cents a
gallon.
   Unleaded gasoline for November delivery climbed to 54.99 cents a
gallon, up 0.19 cent from Friday's close. Contracts for later
delivery of both refined products posted smaller gains.
   West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of crude oil, rose
15 cents to settle at $20.02 a 42-gallon barrel. The contract
closed at $19.87 on Friday, down 9 cents from the previous session.
The December crude contract closed up 17 cents at $19.85 a barrel.
   Traders said prices moved in a narrow range throughout the
session in what might have been the lightest trading day this year.
Three holidays combined to keep trading volume thin _ Columbus Day,
Yom Kippur and Canada's Thanksgiving Day holiday.
   ``It's very quiet,'' said Jack Unger, energy broker with Merrill
Lynch Energy Futures.
   Brendan Dolan, trader with Dean Witter Reynolds Inc., said
heating oil helped push the market higher, despite the thin volume.
   ``It moved up on seasonal factors,'' Dolan said. ``It will
probably continue to move the market out.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
