<FIRST>u f AM-Johnson-Merck     10-09 0246</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Johnson-Merck,0255</SECOND>
<HEAD>Joint Pharmaceutical Venture Agrees To Buy Antacid Producer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A joint venture between two major American
pharmaceutical companies has agreed to buy the over-the-counter
medicine business of a British concern's U.S. subsidiary for about
$450 million, it was announced Monday.
   Johnson &amp; Johnson-Merck Consumer Pharmaceuticals Co. announced
the agreement in principle to buy the over-the counter medicines
business of ICI Americas, the maker of Mylanta antacid and Mylicon
anti-gas products.
   With the acquisition of ICI Americas' over-the-counter business,
Johnson &amp; Johnson-Merck, a joint venture formed in March and based
in Fort Washington, Pa., would become the 14th largest firm in the
United States' over-the-counter medicines market, said John
Doorley, a Merck spokesman.
   ICI Americas is a subsidiary of Imperial Chemical Industries PLC
of Great Britain.
   Johnson &amp; Johnson-Merck says it wants to develop
non-prescription products, mainly from Merck's prescription
medicines, and seek new products outside the two companies. Mylanta
and Mylicon would be the venture's first marketed products.
   F. Robert Kniffin, a spokesman for Johnson &amp; Johnson, said the
venture hoped to sign a final agreement by the end of the year.
Kniffin said ICI Americas would receive cash, other obligations and
U.S. rights to Merck's anti-depressant, Elavil, together worth more
than $450 million.
   Doorley said Johnson &amp; Johnson and Merck would make equal
contributions, but that Merck's cash contribution would be less
because it was giving up rights to Elavil. He would not discuss the
amount of cash involved.
</TEXT>
