<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     10-09 0659</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0688</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soybean Prices Plunge Due to Good Harvest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HERBERT G. McCANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices closed lower Monday as traders
reacted to news that the weekend saw near perfect harvesting
conditions.
   On other markets, cotton prices were sharply lower, precious
metals drifted lower, livestock and pork futures were mixed, energy
futures were higher and coffee prices continued to drift lower.
   Trading on the nation's commodity exchanges was thin due to the
Yom Kippur and Columbus Day holiday.
   Wheat settled 3{ cents to 5\ cents lower with the contract for
delivery in December at $4.06\ a bushel; corn was 2{ cents to 4
cents lower with December at $2.35 a bushel; oats were 3 cents to
3{ cents lower with December at $1.40{ a bushel; and soybeans were
7\ cents to 11} cents lower with November at $5.56} a bushel.
   November and January soybeans drifted to contract lows in light
trading at the Chicago Board of Trade, reflecting the harvest news.
   Adding pressure to prices was the expectation that the U.S.
Department of Agriculture's crop report due out Thursday will have
an upward revision of the crop production estimate, said William
Biedermann, an analyst with Allendale Inc. in Chicago.
   Corn prices were pressured by the belief there will be little
additional business from the Soviet Union. The USDA announced late
Friday that the Soviets have purchased 1.1 million metric tons of
corn.
   There is little prospect of more business from the Soviet Union,
Biedermann said.
   Wheat prices were undermined by a spillover effect from soybeans
and a lack of export demand.
   Cotton prices closed sharply lower on New York's Cotton Exchange
as moderating weather conditions in the delta cotton-growing region
prompted profit-taking by commission houses.
   Weather forecasts had indicated that temperatures would drop
below freezing in crop-growing areas over the weekend. However,
temperatures remained above freezing.
   Cotton was .41 cent to 1.47 cents lower with October at 74.53
cents a pound.
   Precious metal prices were lower on New York's Commodity
Exchange as the dollar showed strength against other major
currencies.
   Gold was 60 cents to $1 lower with October at $363.10 a troy
ounce; silver was 6.7 cents to 8.7 cents lower with October at
$5.05 a troy ounce.
   Oil futures prices finished higher on the New York Mercantile
Exchange, led by a seasonal push in heating oil.
   Traders said prices moved in a narrow range throughout the
session in what might have been the lightest trading day this year.
   West Texas Intermediate was 15 cents to 17 cents higher with
November at $20.02 a barrel; heating oil was .35 cent to .59 ent
higher with November at 58.77 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline was
.05 cent to .19 cent higher with November at 54.99 cents a gallon.
   Coffee prices continued their decline on New York's Coffee,
Sugar &amp; Cocoa Exchange as the market reacts to the failure last
week of the International Coffee Organization to come up with a
price support agreement.
   Prices also were driven down by the abundance of coffee
supplies, said Kim Badenhop, an analyst with Merrill Lynch Capital
Markets Inc in New York.
   Coffee was 1.45 cents to 1.76 cents lower with December at 68.72
cents a pound.
   Livestock futures closed mostly lower and pork futures were
mixed in light trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Cattle futures were underpinned by firmer cash prices, but that
firmness was undermined somewhat by lower beef cut-out prices.
   Pork futures were helped by lighter than anticipated movement to
market of hogs, analysts said.
   Live cattle were .10 cent lower to .28 cent higher with October
at 71.95 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .22 cent lower to .08
cent higher with October at 82.75 a pound; hogs were .02 cent lower
to .60 cent higher with October at 46.60 cents a pound; and frozen
pork bellies were .47 cent to .58 cent lower with February at 46.57
cents a pound.
</TEXT>
