<FILEID>AP-NR-10-09-89 1750EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-USAir     10-09 0385</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-USAir,0399</SECOND>
<HEAD>USAir Stock Rises After Published Report</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   USAir Group Inc. stock climbed in heavy
trading Monday after a published report said a major stockholder,
Steinhardt Partners, was buying more shares and looking into other
options aimed at raising the company's stock price.
   Michael H. Steinhardt, a New York money manager whose firm owns
8.3 percent of the Arlington, Va., based USAir Group, has hired
Wall Street investment banker Wertheim Schroder &amp; Co. to explore
ways to raise the price of the stock, USA Today's Dan Dorfman
reported Monday.
   The newspaper said Steinhardt apparently thinks the stock is
undervalued.
   Two calls to Steinhardt Partners were not returned Monday.
   USAir Group was the most active issue traded on the New York
Stock Exchange on Monday, rising $3.62{ a share to $52.25 on volume
of 1.65 million shares.
   After the stock market closed, USAir said a softening of revenue
and increased expenses will cause significantly lower operating
results for the company in both the third and fourth quarters.
   Expenses are higher than expected because of labor costs and
onetime costs related to its recent merger with Piedmont Airlines,
Chairman Edwin I. Colodny said. In addition, he said Hurricane Hugo
disrupted the USAir system in the Southeast.
   USAir spokeswoman Susan Young said the company had no comment on
the news story about Steinhardt Partners. ``That is a speculative
kind of thing,'' she said.
   Increasing services to overseas markets, selling off a stake in
the business to a foreign investor or a recapitalization plan
involving large stockholder dividends are among the options
Steinhardt is studying, USA Today said.
   The newspaper also said that although there were no takeover
plans, Steinhardt had not ruled out a takeover bid.
   USAir has already girded for possible takeover battles. In
August, in what was described as a friendly deal, the company sold
$358 million worth of a new preferred stock to Berkshire Hathaway,
a firm led by billionaire investor Warren Buffett. That stock could
be converted to at least a 12 percent stake in the company in two
years, according to the deal.
   USAir has also set up an employee stock plan and has boosted its
stock buyback program. Under the buyback program the company hopes
to have about 20 percent of its stock in friendly hands by mid-1990.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
