<FILEID>AP-NR-10-09-89 2019EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Earns-DowJones     10-09 0413</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Earns-Dow Jones,0424</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dow Jones' Profit Down 9.9 Percent in Third Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dow Jones &amp; Co. Inc. on Monday reported a 9.9
percent decline in third-quarter profit, reflecting continued
weakness in financial advertising in its publications and a drop in
net income at a key affiliate.
   The business publishing company said its profit fell to $28.8
million, or 29 cents a share, in the three months ended Sept. 30
from $32 million, or 33 cents a share, in the same period a year
earlier.
   The decline occurred despite a 5.3 percent increase in revenue
to $404.1 million from $383.7 million in the third quarter of 1988.
   Dow Jones attributed the profit decline partly to continued
weakness in advertising at its flagship publication The Wall Street
Journal and its weekly financial newspaper, Barron's. In addition,
the company said, its bottom line was hurt by a 17.6 percent drop
in net income at Telerate Inc., an electronic financial data
service that is 67 percent owned by Dow Jones.
   Profits at Telerate, like Dow Jones a publicly traded company,
tumbled to $19.5 million, or 21 cents a share, from $23.6 million,
or 25 cents a share, in the third quarter of 1988. Most of the loss
came from startup costs for its new foreign-exchange trading
service.
   Separately Monday, Telerate said it is in negotiations to buy
the 50 percent stake that its partner American Telephone &amp;
Telegraph Co. owns in the joint venture Global Transactions
Services Co. Telerate and AT&amp;T began the venture in 1987 to develop
an electronic service for foreign-exchange transactions.
   Telerate is expected to reply on Tuesday to an $18-a-share, or
$576 million, offer from Dow Jones for the remainder of Telerate
that it doesn't already own. The offer, announced last month,
values the entire company at nearly $1.71 billion.
   Dow Jones' net income for the first nine months of the year
jumped 49.7 percent to $277.2 million, or $2.75 a share, from
$185.1 million, or $1.92 a share, in the year-earlier period. The
latest nine-month period included an after-tax gain of $164.1
million, or $1.63 a share, from the sale in January of Dow Jones'
interest in Continental Cablevision Inc.
   In the first nine months of 1988, Dow Jones had an after-tax
gain of $68 million, or 71 cents a share, mainly from the sale of
its book-publishing subsidiary.
   Revenue for the first three quarters rose 4.9 percent to $1.25
billion from $1.19 billion a year earlier.
</TEXT>
