<FILEID>AP-NR-10-09-89 2023EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-TopSecret-Lawsuit     10-09 0389</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Top Secret-Lawsuit,0403</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Rejects Motion To Dismiss Lawsuit Over Top-Secret Contract</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STAMFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A state judge has refused to block a
lawsuit against General Dynamics Corp., which claimed it was immune
from the suit under national security laws.
   Stamford Superior Court Judge Nicholas A. Cioffi said in his
decision, which was filed Friday and released Monday, that only the
federal government _ not a private party _ could invoke national
security privileges to protect itself from lawsuits.
   Norden Systems, a subsidiary of Hartford-based United
Technologies Corp., sued General Dynamics in April after Norden was
dropped from a top-secret program to develop a new generation of
Navy jet fighters.
   General Dynamics, based in St. Louis, is the prime contractor
for the $4 billion Advanced Tactical Aircraft program. It had
awarded a $114 million subcontract to Norden in January 1988 to
develop an in-air radar system for the jet fighter.
   General Dynamics said it canceled the contract because it was
dissatisfied with Norden's work.
   Norden, based in Norwalk, claims it is owed at least $39 million
for the work it did on the radar system. It also claims its
reputation was damaged by the cancellation and that hundreds of
jobs also were eliminated as a result.
   Norden is seeking damages in excess of $15,000 in its lawsuit.
Under Connecticut law, plaintiffs can only specify ranges of
damages they are seeking, not a specific amount.
   General Dynamics argued in court last month that it can't be
sued because the contract dispute involves a top-secret project.
Company attorney Herbert Fenster of Washington, D.C., said that to
defend itself General Dynamics would have to publicly release
top-secret documents. Fenster said the release of such documents
would compromise national security.
   Norden contends it can prove its case without using top-secret
documents.
   General Dynamics' also argued that the Superior Court lacks
jurisdiction over the matter. Cioffi also rejected that claim,
saying: ``This court does have subject matter jurisdiction to
entertain the instant case which is a contract action.''
   Fenster wasn't in his office Monday and couldn't be reached for
a comment, according to a secretary.
   Norden spokesman Scott Brinckerhoff said, ``We're pleased that
this obstacle has been removed and the case can go forward.''
   The Navy has not intervened in the dispute. It has asked only
that national secrets not be disclosed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
