<FIRST>u f AM-WallStreet 2ndLd-Writethru   10-09 0498</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wall Street, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0518</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 12th graf, Other gainers... to CORRECT closing price of
USX.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices kept their recent run of record
highs going Monday with a small advance in slow holiday trading.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 5.89 to 2,791.41,
hitting a new closing high for the fifth consecutive session.
   Advancing issues slightly outnumbered declines in nationwide
trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks, with 705 up, 657
down and 546 unchanged.
   Volume on the floor of the Big Board came to 86.81 million
shares, down from 172.52 million Friday and the lightest total
since a 68.87 million-share day on July 3, which was a session
sandwiched between a weekend and Independence Day.
   Nationwide, consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including
trades in those stocks on regional exchanges and in the
over-the-counter market, totaled 106.27 million shares.
   A quiet day had been expected in the absence of many market
participants for the Columbus Day and Yom Kippur holidays.
   Analysts said those traders who were on hand were apparently
taking a moment to pause and reappraise the outlook for the economy
and interest rates.
   Recent evidence of only sluggish growth in the economy, and a
strong dollar in foreign exchange, have prompted talk of increasing
prospects for an easier Federal Reserve credit policy.
   But many observers have cautioned that the Fed is likely to act
only cautiously and gradually, in keeping with the style of
Chairman Alan Greenspan.
   Computer and technology issues continued their rebound of the
past couple of sessions from a selloff that followed an earnings
disappointment at International Business Machines.
   IBM rose 1} to 109\; Compaq Computer 6 to 104|; Digital
Equipment 1~ to 93{, and Hewlett-Packard 1[ to 51\. Walt Disney was
also jumping, up 6\ at 134[.
   Other gainers among the blue chips included Philip Morris, up }
at 179]; Exxon, up \ at 45|; USX, up [ at 38|, Procter &amp; Gamble, up
2} at 131}, and DuPont, up 1{ at 122.
   Airline stocks were mostly higher on a continued flow of
takeover news and speculation. AMR, being sought by investor Donald
Trump, gained ~ to 104|; USAir jumped 3| to 52\, and Delta Air
Lines was up 1} at 81}.
   Abbott Laboratories picked up | to 67|, traded at new 52-week
highs. The company reported third-quarter earnings of 88 cents a
share, up from 76 cents in the comparable period a year ago.
   As measured by Wilshire Associates' index of more than 5,000
actively traded stocks, the market increased $9.16 billion, or 0.26
percent, in value.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks
gained .40 to 199.34.
   Standard &amp; Poor's industrial index rose 1.27 to 410.49, and
S&amp;P's 500-stock composite index was up 1.02 at 359.80.
   The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market
climbed 2.09 to 485.73. At the American Stock Exchange, the market
value index closed at 396.52, up .59.
</TEXT>
