<FILEID>AP-NR-10-09-89 1844EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Honda     10-09 0442</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Honda,0458</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mr. Honda Visits Detroit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DEARBORN, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soichiro Honda, the founder of the
Japanese automaker that bears his name, dropped by the Henry Ford
Museum on Monday and recalled the day he first saw an automobile _
a Model T he chased down a Japanese road when he was 6.
   ``Every time that Ford car stopped, it left a little bit of an
oil slick underneath and I smelled that oil slick, I enjoyed it
thoroughly and I still remember very vividly the kind of enjoyment
I had by smelling that oil slick,'' the 82-year-old Honda said.
   In addition to the museum visit, where he received a plaque,
Honda was in the Detroit area to be inducted Tuesday into the
Automotive Hall of Fame.
   He talked to reporters in front of a 1983 Honda Accord with a
serial number 001, the first car to be made at the company's
Marysville, Ohio, assembly plant.
   His company was followed by other Japanese automakers in
establishing assembly plants in the United States. Toyota Motor
Corp., Mazda Motor Corp. and Nissan Motor Corp. each have wholly
owned plants on U.S. soil.
   Mitsubishi Motors Corp. is linked with Chrysler Corp. in a joint
venture and Fuji Heavy Industries Inc. and Isuzu Motors Ltd. own a
plant to make Subaru cars and Isuzu trucks.
   Later this year, Honda begins production at its second U.S.
plant, in East Liberty, Ohio. Honda will make Civic and Accord cars
at the two plants.
   But Honda has steered clear of linking itself with a U.S.
automaker. It has a production agreement with the British automaker
Austin Rover, maker of Sterling cars for the U.S. market.
   The company's founder declined to speculate on whether the
company would join forces with any other company in the United
States. ``That never happened during my generation and I cannot
answer what is going to happen in the future,'' he said.
   Honda began his auto career in a Tokyo repair shop at the age of
16. In the 1930s he became involved in racing and in 1937, he
formed a small piston ring company.
   He formed Honda Motor Co. in 1948 and began producing bicycles.
The company entered the auto industry in 1963 and became a U.S.
manufacturer just less than 20 years later.
   Honda has no formal role with the company he founded. ``I
retired from Honda Motor Company 16 years ago. I'm currently
unemployed.''
   Yet his passion for cars and the way they work continues.
   ``What I would really like to do even today is mess up my hands
and work in grease,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891009-0216 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-09-89 2046EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-AMI     10-09 0170</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AMI,0178</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hospital Management Company Accepts Lower Offer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American Medical International Inc.
on Monday accepted an investment group's reduced buyout offer that
values the company at $3 billion, including the assumption of $1.31
billion in debt.
   The investment group, IMA Holdings Corp., which includes
Chicago's Pritzker family and First Boston Corp., last week
withdrew an offer of $3.35 billion for the hospital management
company, saying it would be unable to finance the original tender
offer as expected.
   Under the revised deal, it agreed to pay $26.50 a share in cash
for about 86 percent of American Medical's stock, and securities
for the remainder.
   The original plan had called for IMA Holdings to pay $28 a share
in cash for about 94 percent of American Medical's stock, and
securities for the rest.
   The revised agreement expires Oct. 25.
   American Medical said that until the tender offer expires, it is
reserving itself the option of soliciting, working out and
accepting a better deal for its shareholders.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
