<FILEID>AP-NR-10-09-89 2102EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Disney     10-09 0184</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Disney,0193</SECOND>
<HEAD>Disney Stock Up Sharply on Euro Disneyland Demand</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BURBANK, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Walt Disney Co. stock shot up $6.25 to
close at $134.12{ a share Monday in composite trading, more than
double the price of a year ago.
   Disney spokesman Thomas Deegan declined to comment, but analysts
attributed the jump to heavy demand in Europe for newly issued
shares of stock in Euro Disneyland, the theme park Disney is
developing outside Paris.
   On Oct. 10, 1988, Disney stock traded at $66.37{ per share, its
high for that year.
   Almost all the news about Disney has been good lately.
   The company reported such heavy demand at its new movie-theme
park in Florida that Michael Eisner, Disney's chairman and chief
executive officer, decided to double the park's size.
   Although Disney was not expected to be a force in this past
summer's record-setting movie season, the studio's ``Dead Poets
Society'' and ``Honey, I Shrunk the Kids'' were both hits.
   Disney also is expanding its empire to include an independent
television station, KHJ in Los Angeles, and is in discussions to
launch a record label.
</TEXT>
