<FILEID>AP-NR-10-09-89 2118EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-APSSale     10-09 0146</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-APS Sale,0154</SECOND>
<HEAD>Investment Firm To Buy Auto Parts Chain for $200 Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The New York-based investment firm Clayton &amp;
Dubilier Inc. said Monday it will buy Houston-based A.P.S. Inc., an
auto parts chain, from Wickes Companies Inc. for about $200 million.
   ``This business has great growth protential,'' said Martin H.
Dubilier, chairman of Clayton &amp; Dubilier.
   A.P.S. is a leading distributor of automotive aftermarket parts.
The company provides services to 109 company-owned Big A automotive
parts stores and to about 1,400 independently owned affiliated
jobbers.
   The Big A stores and jobbers sell primarily to independent
professional mechanics, national accounts and automobile owners.
   Dubilier said A.P.S. has had several management and financial
changes in the past five years. Clayton &amp; Dubilier plans to work
with the current management to build a more financially stable
company.
   ``We're financing it for growth,'' Dubilier said.
</TEXT>
