<DOCNO> AP891009-0221 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-09-89 2122EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-RyderLoss     10-09 0283</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Ryder Loss,0294</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ryder To Post A Third-Quarter Loss</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ryder System Inc. will record a $57 million
after-tax charge in the third quarter, resulting in a loss for the
quarter, the transportation and aircraft services company said
Monday.
   The charge includes an adjustment for higher-than-expected
workers' compensation loss reserves, staff and facility reduction
costs, and a loss caused by the the bankruptcy filing of Braniff
Airlines, which had an aircraft maintenance contract with Ryder,
the company said.
   Also included in the charge are a write-down of the carrying
value of unprofitable small businesses in Ryder's Vehicle Leasing &amp;
Services division, anticipated losses from the disposal of surplus
vehicles in that division, and a slow-moving parts inventory in
Ryder's aviation services operation.
   ``We are still dealing with the problems of margin and cost
pressures in the Vehicle Leasing &amp; Services Division and lower auto
production affecting the Automotive Carrier Division,'' said
Ryder's chairman, president and chief executive officer, M. Anthony
Burns.
   Ryder is expected to report the quarterly loss and revenue
figures shortly.
   For 1988's third quarter, Ryder earned $55.2 million on revenue
of $1.26 billion. Revenue for the 12 months ended June 30 totaled
$5.1 billion.
   The company also announced Monday the sale of most of its
Insurance Management Services division to Skandia International
Insurance Corp. of Stockholm, Sweden.
   The sale price was not disclosed. The deal is expected to close
by year's end, Burns said.
   ``The Insurance Management Services division has been a
profitable part of Ryder System,'' Burns said. ``However, Ryder's
strategy in the future will be to concentrate on our transportation
businesses.''
   Miami-based Ryder operates in three areas: motor vehicle
leasing, new-car transportation and aviation services.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
