<FILEID>AP-NR-10-09-89 2249EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Australia-Shearson     10-09 0242</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Australia-Shearson,0252</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shearson To Cut Back Australian Operations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SYDNEY, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. said Monday
it will close its Australian interbank foreign exchange, financial
futures and stock brokerage activities.
   The New York-based investment house said the restructuring is
part of a shakeout among Australian stock brokerages and
foreign-exchange institutions, which are ``suffering from
continuing increased competition and shrinking profit margins.''
   An increase in the number of foreign commercial banks,
investment banks and brokerages here has exacerbated the
competition for business in the financial industry.
   ``It was decided we would be far better to focus our resources
in the areas in which we can provide the most added value to
clients from a local base and to move out of the Australian
interbank foreign exchange market and Australian-sourced broking
areas,'' Ken Allen, chairman of Shearson's Australian operations,
said in a statement Monday.
   Allen said the refocusing follows a review of Shearson's
worldwide operations.
   ``We will service the foreign exchange, U.S. equity and
financial futures requirements of our institutional clients from
our major locations in New York, Tokyo and London,'' Allen said.
``(That) appears to be the most appropriate course of action given
the preference of larger institutions to look for advice directly
from the offshore capital markets.''
   The company said about 20 sales and trading employees will be
offered a severance package or relocation.
   Shearson, which is majority owned by American Express Co.,
started business in Australia in 1987.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
